<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 00:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement on African Diamond Ban  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council imposed a diamond ban
Wednesday on Sierra Leone's rebels in a bid to strangle their
ability to finance a civil war that has already cost the lives of
tens of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   The embargo is for an initial 18 months. The council could
decide to extend it if the government hasn't reasserted its
authority over Sierra Leone's diamond mines, 90 percent of which
remain in rebel hands.
</P>
<P>
   Mali abstained from the vote, saying it opposed the resolution's
reference to illegal diamonds being shipped through Liberia. Mali's
U.N. ambassador, Moctar Ouane, said the reference was
''unacceptable'' because West African nations have not completed an
investigation into the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   But Sierra Leone's U.N. ambassador, Ibrahim Kamara, hailed the
council's willingness to name names and to acknowledge that Sierra
Leone's war wasn't about ideology or tribal differences but rather
about diamonds and people trying to make illegal profit off them.
</P>
<P>
   ''At last, the Security Council has come to realize that the war
in Sierra Leone is cast in gemstones,'' Kamara told the council.
</P>
<P>
   Britain sponsored the resolution as a way to reign in rebels of
the Revolutionary United Front, who restarted Sierra Leone's civil
war in May by taking 500 U.N. peacekeepers hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The diamond embargo makes it illegal to buy Sierra Leone
diamonds, except those that have a certificate of origin from the
government. Since there is no certification process yet in place,
the ban would initially cover all diamond sales.
</P>
<P>
   The London-based organization Global Witness reported in October
that rebels earned $200 million a year from 1991 to 1999 in illicit
diamond sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have begun a system which will immediately make it more
expensive and more difficult for the traders to deal in conflict
diamonds -- some people call them blood diamonds -- from Sierra
Leone,'' British Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the embargo would be followed up with other resolutions
on prosecuting Sankoh and other rebel members -- perhaps even with
an international tribunal -- and strengthening the U.N. peacekeeping
mission in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The council vote, he said, would ''give people hope in Sierra
Leone that the world is actually taking some action that is going
to mean a bit of peace and prosperity for them in I hope the not
too distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote had been held up by disputes over whether to
set a time limit for the diamond embargo and whether to name
Liberia as a transit point for illicit diamond sales.
</P>
<P>
   France had pressed for a time limit, while the United States and
Britain initially sought an open-ended ban.
</P>
<P>
   The United States voted for the resolution, but Deputy U.S.
Ambassador Nancy Soderberg said Washington did so with a
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States strongly believes that sanctions, to have
meaning and force, must be tied to a change in the behavior that
prompts imposition of sanctions in the first place -- not an
arbitrary date on the calendar,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution expresses concern at reports that diamonds were
being shipped through Liberian ''territory'' -- a softening of the
original draft which referred more directly to the Liberian
government.
</P>
<P>
   Council members were warned Friday by Oluyemi Adeniji, the top
U.N. envoy in Sierra Leone, against naming Liberia as a conduit for
the diamonds because the country's president, Charles Taylor, is
trying to free 222 U.N. peacekeepers from India and 11 unarmed U.N.
observers still surrounded by rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is Sankoh's closest ally and west African governments and
the United Nations relied on him to negotiate freedom for some 500
U.N. peacekeepers held hostage in Sierra Leone for several weeks by
the rebels in May.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the diamond ban, the resolution calls for an
exploratory hearing to be held in New York to assess the role that
diamonds have played in the Sierra Leone conflict. And it calls for
a panel of experts to examine the link between the sale of diamonds
and the purchase of arms in Sierra Leone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
