<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer admits telling judge and FBI that bogus death threat was real </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A defense lawyer from Rhode Island admits he
knew a death threat he got was phony when he reported it to a
federal judge and FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had charged that the lawyer, John B. Webster,
obstructed justice by inventing the death threat against himself to
get favorable treatment for a client on trial here.
</P>
<P>
   That charge, and three others in an April indictment are to be
dropped in return for Webster's guilty plea Wednesday to a single
count of making a false statement.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Webster's client, Victor P. Samaha, and a friend of
Samaha's, Vincent Mansolillo, admitted roles in the scheme and
agreed to testify against Webster. Both are from Warwick, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Webster, 40, of Coventry, R.I., whose practice is in Warwick, is
likely to be disbarred, said his lawyer, John D. Arseneault and
Rhode Island authorities. Arseneault said they will fight to keep
his license.
</P>
<P>
   Webster faces up to five years in prison and a fine of up to
$250,000 when sentenced Sept. 26 by U.S. District Judge Alfred J.
Lechner Jr. The actual term is likely to be less than two years,
without parole, under sentencing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious charge in the indictment was the obstruction
charge, which carries up to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stemmed from Samaha's trial last year, in which
Samaha was convicted Nov. 11 of stock fraud along with another
former broker at L.C. Wegard &AMP; Co. Fourteen other brokers had
already pleaded guilty to related charges of using ''boiler room''
tactics to push low-cost, high-risk stocks on unsuspecting buyers.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal authorities have asserted for years that
Wegard was one of two now-shuttered brokerages secretly controlled
by disgraced penny-stock tycoon Robert E. Brennan after he closed
his flagship operation, First Jersey Securities Inc. in the late
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, formerly of Brielle, N.J., and now living in Juno
Beach, Fla., settled a lawsuit brought by New Jersey last year by
agreeing to pay $45 million to compensate investors.
</P>
<P>
   He denied wrongdoing but consented to a finding that he used
''substantial influence'' at the two brokerages to make
''unreasonably excessive profits'' in low-cost, high-risk stocks in
which he held an undisclosed interest from 1988-95.
</P>
<P>
   During Samaha's trial, Webster raised a defense that Brennan and
others - not Samaha - were behind a scheme to cheat Wegard
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors objected, claiming it was irrelevant, and U.S.
District Judge William G. Bassler issued a tentative ruling in
their favor, but asked both sides for legal briefs on the relevance
of the ''Brennan Conspiracy'' theory.
</P>
<P>
   While the issue was pending, a story describing the objection
appeared in The Star-Ledger of Newark on Oct. 14, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Webster admitted that he and Samaha that night discussed a
scenario in which someone would threaten the lawyer in an effort to
convince Bassler to admit evidence of the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, this message was recorded on Webster's cell
phone voice mail: ''Webster, you mention Robert Brennan's name in
court again, you're not going to make it home from New York
alive,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   He reported it that night to federal prosecutors and the FBI but
learned the next morning from Samaha that the call was bogus,
Arseneault said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Webster went to court and met with Bassler, and
later played the message for FBI agents, he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew that Samaha had arranged the threat,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   Webster declined to speak outside court.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the scenario discussed with Samaha, Arseneault said
''perhaps (Webster) should have been more vociferous in opposing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansolillo admitted he had somebody make the threatening call,
telling a judge that he had Stephen Cloutier make the call from
Providence, R.I. Cloutier has not been charged. Samaha admitted
conspiring to obstruct justice. They await sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Webster was admitted to the Rhode Island bar in 1987. He was
admitted to the Ohio bar in 1984, but said that license is
inactive.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
