<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newhouse family buys four dailies in N.J. and Pa.  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The Newhouse family, which publishes the
state's largest newspaper, expanded its presence in New Jersey with
the purchase of three daily newspapers and a Pennsylvania paper
with a strong New Jersey readership.
</P>
<P>
   Penn Jersey Advance Inc., a subsidiary of Newhouse's Advance
Publications, bought The Gloucester County Times in Woodbury,
Today's Sunbeam in Salem, the Bridgeton Evening News and the
Express-Times in Easton, Pa., from MediaNews Group Inc. of Denver.
It also purchased a group of 40 weekly newspapers in both states.
</P>
<P>
   The companies did not disclose the purchase price in their
announcement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, which took place June 30, gives Newhouse six of New
Jersey's 18 daily newspapers and gives it a presence in the
suburban Philadelphia market. In addition to the Star-Ledger, the
state's largest newspaper, New York-based Advance owns The Jersey
Journal in Jersey City and The Times of Trenton. Approximately 40
percent of the Easton newspaper's daily circulation of 50,641 also
comes from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The sale follows other recent consolidation of newspaper
ownership. In the past 2 1/2 years Gannett Co. Inc., of Arlington,
Va., purchased four papers, including Asbury Park Press of Neptune,
to give it a total of seven New Jersey newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The companies together account for more than 70 percent of the
state's daily newspaper circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Advance, led by the Star-Ledger's daily circulation of 407,129,
now accounts for a combined daily circulation of 577,883 in New
Jersey. The combined circulation of Gannett's newspapers is
443,551, according to figures published in the latest edition of
Editor &AMP; Publisher Yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   MediaNews Group also sold newspaper operations in New Jersey and
Pennsylvania to Advance. Those holdings include a group of 40
weeklies with a combined circulation of 548,178 published in Union,
Somerset, Warren and Hunterdon counties in New Jersey plus
Northampton and Lehigh counties in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ''While this transaction was one of the most difficult decisions
MediaNews Group has ever made, we believe these newspapers will fit
much better with Advance than MediaNews,'' said president and CEO
William Dean Singleton. ''The Newhouse family is New Jersey's
largest newspaper publisher and the critical mass they bring to
these newspapers will add much value to the newspapers, their
readers, advertisers and employees.''
</P>
<P>
   MediaNews said it would use proceeds of the sales in markets
that had a better strategic fit. The nation's seventh-largest
newspaper company, MediaNews publishes 47 daily newspapers and 83
non-daily publications in 12 states, with a circulation of about 2
million.
</P>
<P>
   ''Advance is proud to acquire a group of outstanding newspapers
in fine markets that we know well,'' said Donald E. Newhouse,
president of Advance Publications. ''We admire Dean Singleton's
vision and leadership in building these publications, and
developing impressive teams to run them successfully. We plan to
continue his focus on serving the newspapers' readers and
advertisers and their communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Advance Publications is the nation's third largest newspaper
company with a combined circulation of 3 million and holdings that
include The Plain Dealer of Cleveland, the Portland (Ore.)
Oregonian and Conde Nast magazines, including the New Yorker,
Vanity Fair and Gourmet. Advance publishes 23 daily newspapers and
32 nondaily newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
