<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devil Rays, Tigers Lose Smith, Fick  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Tampa Bay's Bobby Smith and
Detroit's Robert Fick are expected to be sidelined 6-8 weeks after
colliding on a play at first base during the Devil Rays' 4-1
victory over the Tigers on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Smith hit a sharp grounder that third baseman Dean Palmer dove
to stop before scrambling to his feet and throwing to first where
Fick -- by that time straddling the bag -- caught the ball on one hop
as Smith toppled over him.
</P>
<P>
   Both players went down, but left the field on their own power.
Smith was credited with an RBI single that tied the game 1-1 in the
third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just lost the bag. I was watching Dean,'' Fick said. ''I was
kind of shocked ... I knew something was wrong from the way my neck
felt. I couldn't throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who sprained the medial collateral ligament in his right
knee, was hitting .311 with three homers and 14 RBIs in 20 games
since being called up from Triple-A Durham.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can never predict anything,'' Devil Rays manager Larry
Rothschild said. ''He gets his chance, takes advantage of it and
then this happens. It's just one of those things that you go
through. He has been through enough this year and hopefully he
comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   Fick, batting .250 with two homers and 18 RBIs in 50 games,
separated his right shoulder. He spent time on the disabled list
last year with a left shoulder strain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
