<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Army Declares Exclusion Zone  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL ALEXANDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Fiji's military stepped up the pressure on
rebels holding 27 hostages in Parliament, closing off access to the
area Thursday and giving two days for scores of rebel supporters to
leave the complex in return for amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Officials insisted the declaration of a military exclusion zone
around the parliament complex was not a prelude to an operation to
free the hostages -- who include the former prime minister and
members of his government. But they expressed frustration with the
standoff that has dragged on for 47 days.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not the first step toward a military option,'' Lt.
Col. Filipo Tarakinikini said at a news conference. ''This is just
a step to try to resolve a situation that has gone on too long.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the military still hoped for a peaceful conclusion to
the crisis, but was not willing to let rebel leader George Speight
''dictate'' its actions and that more drastic measures have not
been ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   ''There might have to be a price to be paid and we are willing
to pay it for the sake of the nation,'' Tarakinikini said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there were some signs of movement in the standoff,
with preliminary talks held between the two sides for the first
time since June 25, when a tentative agreement between rebels and
Fiji's military rulers collapsed at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Details were sparse. Rebel spokesman Jo Nata told reporters that
talks that began Thursday morning and continued into the afternoon
likely were ''very, very exploratory.''
</P>
<P>
   Speight, who claims he has popular support for his goal of
giving priority to the rights of indigenous Fijians over those of
the ethnic Indian minority, has warned that the hostages could be
harmed if the military halts access to the compound or cuts off
utilities, as Tarakinikini said was a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''It must be impressed upon the military that the blockade of
supplies will have direct implications on the security and the life
of the people who are under our care,'' Nata said by telephone from
inside the complex to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Under a drenching rain, soldiers manning the exclusive zone
seemed fairly relaxed as midnight passed and the zone order took
effect in the early hours Thursday. Under the orders, entry to the
complex is barred except to food supplies. Until now, supporters of
the rebels had been allowed in and out of the parliament complex
with little impediment, and Speight also left and re-entered
several times.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel spokesman Nata claimed up to 3,000 supporters were in and
around the compound -- a figure that appeared somewhat inflated. He
said rebels would tell all the supporters that they were free to
leave. ''But I am confident that none will leave,'' Nata said.
</P>
<P>
   Speight supporters occupied the airport at Labasa, on the
northern island of Vanua Levu, for two hours Thursday morning
before leaving peacefully, a control tower official said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was pretty calm,'' he told The Associated Press by
telephone. ''They apparently wanted to give some backing to Speight
and those who were involved in the thing at the military base.''
</P>
<P>
   Two soldiers seized weapons from the base at Labasa on Tuesday
before returning them a day later. Tarakinikini blamed local chiefs
for instigating that incident and said they were capable of more
''disturbances.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a drenching rain, soldiers manning the numerous
checkpoints on the streets around Parliament seemed fairly relaxed
as the exclusion zone order took effect at midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Commodore Frank Bainimarama, who assumed power 10 days after the
coup, has been reluctant to take strong action as long as the
hostages were not harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the military support the rebel's objective of ensuring
that the rights of indigenous Fijians come first. Some members of
the crack Counter-Revolutionary Warfare unit have been among those
guarding the compound since it was stormed on May 19 and the
government of Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry -- the first Fijian
of Indian ancestry to lead the country -- was taken hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Indians generally have prospered since they were brought to Fiji
more than a century ago by English colonialists seeking indentured
laborers for rich sugar cane fields. They make up 44 percent of the
population, and have become dominant in commerce and now politics,
sparking resentment among the 51 percent indigenous Fijians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
