<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Becomes Leader in Free Trade  </HEADLINE>
By ELLIOT SPAGAT
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- As he prepares to leave office Dec. 1,
President Ernesto Zedillo is making Mexico one of the world's most
avid practitioners of free trade.
</P>
<P>
   The latest string of deals -- including those with Israel,
Honduras and the European Union -- puts Mexico in the major leagues
of the world's most enthusiastic backers of bilateral free trade
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anyone who's willing to sign one, they'll do it,'' said Sidney
Weintraub of the Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Vicente Fox, whose victory in Sunday's elections
ended the 71-year-rule of Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary
Party, has embraced the agreements and said earlier this week that
Mexico should increase trade with its new partners.
</P>
<P>
   Free trade agreements took effect Saturday with the European
Union and Israel. Mexico signed its ninth one last week with
Guatemala, El Salvador and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are scheduled to begin this week with Switzerland,
Iceland, Norway and Lichtenstein on a free trade agreement, and the
Zedillo administration hopes to clinch one with Panama before its
term ends Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The government recently agreed to begin talks with Singapore,
setting the stage for its first free trade agreement in Asia. It
held exploratory talks with Japan and floated the idea of an
agreement with the Mercosur trading bloc of Brazil, Argentina,
Uruguay and Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   The trade pacts have sparked an export boom that has allowed
Mexico to recover from its 1995 economic meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the government has exacerbated income
disparities by benefitting sectors plugged into the global economy
and leaving behind those unprepared to compete, most notably grain
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole approach is that those who are fit to compete at the
international level will be successful and those who are not will
die,'' said Carlos Heredia, a congressional deputy of the leftist
Democratic Revolution Party.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo last week recited a familiar mantra to hundreds of
business leaders: Free trade alleviates poverty, makes available
higher-quality goods at lower prices, and creates jobs. The
government says that nearly half the 3.3 million jobs created in
Mexico in the past five years are export-related and that export
jobs pay better.
</P>
<P>
   ''Examples of countries that have overcome economic backwardness
in the last century are well-documented, and all of them have
pursued a common strategy: acceptance of free trade, investment and
technology,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should always be aware that open economies build bridges to
the rest of the world, while closed economies become isolated and
immobile.''
</P>
<P>
   Exports accounted for nearly 30 percent of Mexico's gross
domestic product last year, up from 13 percent in 1993, the year
before the North American Free Trade Agreement with the United
States and Canada took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's motive for the recent agreements is simple: to be less
dependent on the United States, the destination for 88 percent of
its exports last year. Two-way trade between Mexico and the United
States has tripled under Nafta to $225.9 billion last year from
$88.1 billion in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive, said Mexico
should try to expand Nafta to encompass free movement of people and
a common monetary policy, cautioning that it would take 20 to 30
years. The common market should include other Latin American
countries, starting with the Mercosur bloc, he told foreign
correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's most promising agreement is with the 15-nation European
Union, a bloc of 375 million consumers. It took only a year to
negotiate the far-reaching agreement to dismantle most trade
barriers by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans agreed to lift tariffs on goods covering 82
percent of Mexican manufacturing imports immediately, with the rest
to be scrapped by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, which traditionally runs a trade deficit with Europe,
received more lenient terms. It agreed to lift tariffs on goods
representing 47 percent of European Union manufacturing imports
immediately, with the rest gradually by 2007. All tariffs will be
capped at 5 percent in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and business leaders don't expect Mexico's new trade
agreements to significantly lessen its dependence on the United
States. Still, the European Union may recapture its share of the
Mexican market lost under Nafta.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union, Mexico's second-largest trading partner,
accounted for 6.5 percent of Mexico's trade last year, down from 9
percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Nafta, Israel, the European Union and Central
America's ''Northern Triangle,'' Mexico has signed free trade
agreements since 1992 with Chile, Colombia and Venezuela, Bolivia,
Costa Rica and Nicaragua.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 0131 </TRAILER>
