<DOCNO> APW20000706.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers' Kreuter Drops Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Los Angeles Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter, the
central figure in a brawl with Wrigley Field fans, dropped his
appeal and began serving his eight-game suspension Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter will miss the final five games before the All-Star break
and then the first three games after.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't want to drop the appeal, but felt it was in
the best interests of the Dodgers. If his appeal was denied, it
would have forced Todd Hundley to catch eight straight games. This
will give Hundley three days of rest during the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like I needed to appeal because I wasn't happy with the
outcome in the first place,'' Kreuter said. ''But I want to be a
team player and do what's best for the ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   The brawl on May 16 started when Kreuter said a fan struck him
in the back of the head and grabbed his cap. Kreuter went into the
stands and his teammates and coaches followed. It triggered a brawl
that delayed the game for nine minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Beeston, baseball's chief operating officer, upheld the
eight-game suspension issued by Frank Robinson, baseball's new head
of discipline. Kreuter then appealed to commissioner Bud Selig.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 0143 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000706.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers 7, Padres 5  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Todd Hundley hit a tying three-run homer in the
sixth and Eric Karros a game-winning two-run shot in the eighth as
the Los Angeles Dodgers rallied from a five-run deficit to beat the
San Diego Padres 7-5 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Dodgers' runs scored on four homers. Starting pitcher
Darren Dreifort started Los Angeles' comeback with a solo homer in
the fifth, but he didn't get the decision. That went to Antonio
Osuna (1-4), who pitched two scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers trailing 5-2, Padres rookie starter Brian
Tollberg walked Shawn Green leading off the sixth and made way for
Carlos Reyes, who walked Karros and then gave up Hundley's
three-run homer that tied it at 5.
</P>
<P>
   Green hit a leadoff single in the eighth off Matt Whiteside
(2-2) and Karros followed with his 24th homer.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's homer was a 407-foot shot off Tollberg into the seats
in left field, the third of his career and the first since last
Aug. 8 at New York. Mark Grudzielanek homered with two outs in the
fifth, cutting the Padres' lead to 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Kory DeHaan hit his first homer and had his first
three-hit game for the Padres. Ryan Klesko accounted for all three
of San Diego's runs in the first inning, hitting a two-run double
down the right-field line and scoring with two outs on the back end
of a double steal.
</P>
<P>
   DeHaan singled in his first two at-bats before hitting an
opposite field homer off Dreifort with two outs in the fourth for a
5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tollberg, who won his first two starts, lasted just five innings
for the second straight start. He allowed three runs and seven
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort remained 0-5 lifetime against the Padres. He gave up
five runs and 10 hits in five innings, struck out eight and walked
one.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego opened the first with singles by Al Martin and DeHaan,
with both scoring on Klesko's double. Carlos Hernandez drew a
two-out walk and stole second. Second baseman Grudzielanek fell
down when he fielded the throw from Hundley, allowing Klesko to
score. DeHaan hit an RBI single in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters got his second save in as many chances.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Hernandez, the Padres' catcher, left after the third with a
mild lower back strain. ... The Dodgers promoted OF Mike Metcalfe
from Triple-A Albuquerque and he started in center. Metcalfe
appeared in four games with the Dodgers in 1998. To make room for
Metcalfe, OF Shawn Gilbert was designated for assignment. ...
Dodgers RHP Kevin Brown, who was added to the All-Star team along
with OF Gary Sheffield, had his scheduled start pushed back to
Thursday due to a strained back. ... Closer Trevor Hoffman will be
San Diego's lone All-Star.
</P>
</TEXT>
