<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners 6, Angels 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Alex Rodriguez drove in Seattle's first
three runs with two homers, including a 455-foot, go-ahead shot in
the fifth, as the Mariners beat the Anaheim Angels 6-4 Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell hit a three-run homer for the Mariners, who extended
their AL West lead to 3&AMP;frac12; games over Oakland and seven over the
third-place Angels.
</P>
<P>
   John Halama (8-4) allowed four runs -- two earned -- and nine hits
in 5 2-3 innings. The left-hander, who lost four of his previous
five decisions following a 6-0 start, struck out six and walked
one.
</P>
<P>
   Kazuhiro Sasaki got three outs for his 18th save in 20 chances,
and eighth in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle led 6-2 in the sixth before RBI singles by Edgard
Clemente -- his fourth RBI in 58 at-bats -- and Darin Erstad, who hit
a high chopper off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, relegated to DH duty for the second straight game
because of a stiff back, had three RBIs including a two-run double
in the second inning. The Angels' leadoff hitter, added to the
All-Star team earlier in the day, leads the majors with 135 hits
and 44 multihit games.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cooper (3-3), coming off a three-hitter against Oakland,
was chased during a four-run fifth that included Rodriguez's 24th
homer and Bell's sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who didn't allow a homer in 28 1-3 innings over his
previous four starts, allowed six runs and nine hits in 4 1-3
innings as the Mariners won for the 14th time in 18 games,
including 11 of 16 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez homered in the first for a 2-0 lead, but Anaheim tied
it in the second when Erstad doubled after second baseman Mark
McLemore dropped Bengie Molina's popup for an error.
</P>
<P>
Notes: All three outs in the eighth against Seattle reliever Brett
Tomko were caught on the warning track. The only batter who reached
safely was Adam Kennedy, on a bloop double. ... Mariners RHP Gil
Meche was optioned to Triple-A Tacoma, allowing him to pitch on
Sunday instead of missing his regular turn during the All-Star
break. Jamie Moyer is scheduled to start Sunday for Seattle against
the Dodgers. ... INF Carlos Guillen was recalled from Tacoma. ...
Edgar Martinez failed to drive in a run for the first time in 10
games. ... Aaron Sele was the first RHP in the Mariners' 24-year
history to be selected for the All-Star game.
</P>
</TEXT>
