<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wust Wins Tour de France 5th Stage  </HEADLINE>
By IAN PHILLIPS
<TEXT>
<P>
   VITRE, France (AP) -- With a quarter of the Tour de France
virtually over, the race is looking good for past winners Lance
Armstrong, Marco Pantani and Jan Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   The three men won the 1999, 1998 and 1997 tours, and despite
failing to win a stage this year, they are sitting just behind the
leaders, confident as the race starts to head south toward the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who rides for the U.S. Postal Service, is undoubtedly
in the best position of the three, with few question marks hanging
over his form and fitness.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Texan is third in the overall standings, 14
seconds behind France's Laurent Jalabert, who has held the leader's
yellow jersey for two days. His camp says he's holding back until
the Pyrenees mountains, where he hopes to take control of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich, a 26-year-old rider for Deutsche Telekom, should also
thrive in the mountains. As so often before, he has had weight
problems coming into the race, and a crash diet has raised
questions about his stamina. But the German has made it to the
podium all three times he has taken part in the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   He's currently 12th, 57 seconds behind Jalabert.
</P>
<P>
   The most unpredictable of the three is Pantani, who is
languishing in 79th place, 5 minutes, 26 seconds behind Jalabert.
But given the 30-year-old Italian's prowess in the mountain stages,
few are counting him out. His rivals know from experience that he
could wipe away a deficit with one trademark burst on the high
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The first mountain stage is on Monday in the Pyrenees. Later,
they head to the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the stage is set for sprint specialists.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Germany's Marcel Wust took the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   In a sprint finish in the medieval town of Vitre in Brittany,
the Festina rider narrowly beat compatriot Erik Zabel of Deutsche
Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Wust won by inches after a late burst. He clocked a time of 4
hours, 19 minutes, 5 seconds. Italy's Stefano Zanini of the Mapei
team was third.
</P>
<P>
   The riders had to withstand rain and wind for most of the
125-mile trek from Vannes on the Atlantic coast to Vitre. Most of
the course was flat except for four climbs.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong finished in 25th place and trimmed 10 seconds off
Jalabert's advantage, but remained in third. He is now 14 seconds
behind the Frenchman.
</P>
<P>
   Jalabert, wearing yellow for the first time in five years, was
59th, but retained the yellow jersey going into Thursday's stage.
Spain's David Canada of Once is second.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's stage covers 123 miles from Vitre to Tours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 0147 </TRAILER>
