<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protestants Rioting in N. Ireland  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Helicopters, army patrols and
sporadic rain dampened down violence in Northern Ireland early
Thursday, but failed to extinguish the Protestant rage that has
sparked four nights of rioting in the British-controlled province.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters hovered low over potential trouble-spots in Belfast
and British soldiers patrolled the streets of the city for the
first time in a year. Security forces sought to contain violence by
hard-line Protestants determined to overturn a ban on an Orange
Order march through hostile Catholic turf.
</P>
<P>
   British army headquarters reported on Wednesday that security
forces had contained 61 riots in Northern Ireland in the previous
24 hours -- more, the army communique said, than in all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And the province's chief policeman, Royal Ulster Constabulary
Chief Constable Ronnie Flanagan, warned that Protestant extremists
planned to attack his officers with guns and bombs. Intelligence
indicated the attacks would ''include the use of blast bombs and
firearms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, police exchanged fire with gunmen in a Protestant
area of north Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Protestants blocked more than a dozen roads
simultaneously at Wednesday evening's rush hour, causing one of the
worst traffic jams Belfast has ever seen. Motorists were trapped on
some gridlocked streets for two hours. Roadblocks also disrupted
traffic in several other towns around the province.
</P>
<P>
   As those protests subsided, masked youths began tossing gasoline
bombs at police armored cars and hijacking vehicles, including a
bus. Police said three officers suffered minor cuts and burns.
</P>
<P>
   Black smoke from burning vehicles stained the evening sky in
south-central Belfast, where Protestant youths also pounded drums
and played anti-Catholic tunes on flutes. British army surveillance
helicopters hovered over the scenes of worst trouble. Sporadic
fireworks explosions and wailing police sirens continued in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Orange Order, Northern Ireland's once-dominant
Protestant brotherhood, insisted they weren't responsible for the
violence. But they refused to halt any protests unless authorities
let them parade Sunday down Garvaghy Road, the main Catholic
section of Portadown, an overwhelmingly Protestant town 30 miles to
the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics in isolated districts complained that the Royal Ulster
Constabulary -- the predominantly Protestant police force and itself
the primary target for violence -- wasn't doing enough to protect
them. Several Catholic families in north Belfast reported having to
evacuate their homes after Protestants shouted death threats
outside and broke windows.
</P>
<P>
   The British army in response deployed about 100 soldiers into
north Belfast to support police units there. It was the army's
first deployment in Belfast since last July, when tensions over
traditional Protestant marches produced little trouble.
</P>
<P>
   At the Drumcree Anglican church near Portadown, a long-standing
flashpoint along the Orangemen's planned marching route, the
situation was calmer Wednesday. Army engineers adopted a previously
used tactic -- erecting a 20-foot-high steel wall across the
entrance to the Garvaghy Road, where Protestant marches have been
blocked since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters burned tires against their side of the barricade,
sending acrid black smoke billowing back toward the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not employ the water cannon used to disperse the
crowd Tuesday, when 14 officers were reported wounded after being
bombarded with gasoline bombs, firecrackers, slingshot projectiles
and even acid.
</P>
<P>
   ''Petrol bombs, fireworks, ball bearings and acid squirted at
the police -- Those are not the weapons of democrats or legitimate
protest. They are the weapons of the bully, and the bully will not
have his way,'' said Britain's minister for Northern Ireland, Peter
Mandelson.
</P>
<P>
   This week's substantial Protestant rebellion against British
authority reflects immediate anger at being forced to concede
symbolic ground to Catholics, as well as wider opposition to key
sections of Northern Ireland's 2-year-old peace accord that have
taken shape in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell, who helped broker the accord,
said Wednesday in Belfast that he still believed ''the course for
Northern Ireland has been set irreversibly on the path for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ''These are tense days and nights. No one should
be unrealistic enough to think it will be risk- or trouble-free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 0214 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000706.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trinidad's Boldon Wins Sprint Double  </HEADLINE>
By CLARE NULLIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Trinidad's Ato Boldon set a fast
standard in an increasingly thrilling pre-Olympic summer, recording
a double at 100 and 200 meters at the Athletissima Grand Prix track
meet.
</P>
<P>
   As he ran past his rivals Wednesday, Boldon's thoughts were with
his absent friends and rivals, 100-meter world champion Maurice
Greene and reigning 200-meter champion Michael Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   '' I'm going to fight Greene and Johnson in Sydney to get the
gold,'' Boldon, a bronze medalist at the Olympics in Atlanta, said
after dancing around the stadium in front of a hugely appreciative
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Boldon recorded the second-fastest time of the year with 9.95 in
the 100 -- behind Greene's 9.91. Boldon's 19.91 in the 200 was
third-fastest this year. Johnson posted a wind-assisted 19.71 in
Pietersburg in March and 19.91 in Seville in June.
</P>
<P>
   Boldon was forced out of last year's worlds due to injury and
has shown continuous improvement since returning to the track this
season.
</P>
<P>
   But 100-meter Olympic champion Donovan Bailey of Canada -- aiming
to match last week's promising 9.98 time in Lucerne -- managed only
a fifth-place finish at 10.12 . Bailey has had mixed results since
suffering a career-threatening Achilles' tendon injury almost two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what went wrong,'' said Bailey, alternating
between disgust and disbelief. ''I wasn't running my race. I never
ran any part of that race. None. Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic gold medalist and two-time World Champion Allen Johnson
dazzled in the 100-meter hurdles, plunging over the finish line in
this season's quickest time of 13.06.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of ideal weather conditions and the famously
fast Pontaise track, the 29-year-old American sliced 0.04 seconds
off his own previous seasonal best.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow American Gail Devers, three-time world 100-meter hurdles
champion, was timed in 12.60 to beat Nigeria's Glory Alozie. But
she finished a weary seventh in 100 meters, .39 behind Greek winner
Ekaterina Thanou.
</P>
<P>
   Double Olympic champion Marie Jose Perec of France, meanwhile,
made a strong comeback, finishing second behind Debbie Ferguson of
the Bahamas in the women's 200, her first race in almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   Perec, who won a historic double gold in the 200 and 400 in
Atlanta, has been plagued by a rare blood virus that forced her to
miss all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''After everything I've had to go through, it's superb,'' a
radiant -- and relieved -- Perec said. ''You always have a sense of
disappointment when you finish second, but I feel good. I expected
to achieve this level, so there's no surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Perec said she had no illusions about the huge challenge facing
her when she makes her reappearance before her home crowd in the
more demanding 400 in Nice on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Six-time pole vault world champion Sergei Bubka of Ukraine also
flunked his return following surgery on his Achilles' tendon last
season and failed to clear the opening height of 18 feet, 4&AMP;frac12;
inches.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time world champion Cathy Freeman of Australia took
advantage of the swift conditions to record the season's top
performance in the women's 400, clinching her 38th victory in 39
finals since the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, who won the world 400 title in Seville last August,
easily outdistanced the field and improved on American Marion
Jones' previous season best by .03 seconds. The Australian has won
every 400 she's entered this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy it's the world's leading time this year,'' said
Freeman, who will now focus on training and not compete again until
the Golden League in Oslo on July 28.
</P>
<P>
   Athletissima -- which celebrated its 25th anniversary -- isn't
part of the lucrative Golden League. Many top American athletes
therefore preferred to train at home for the upcoming U.S. Olympic
trials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 0221 </TRAILER>
