<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Quake Rattles Japan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A moderate earthquake with a preliminary magnitude
of 5.2 struck off Japan's northeastern coast Thursday afternoon,
and there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Meteorological Agency said the center of the quake was 19
miles below the seabed off the coast of Ibaraki state, about 62
miles northeast of Tokyo. It hit just after 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuneaki Anami, an official of the Agency's Seismological and
Volcanological Department, said the Pacific earthquake had ''no
connection'' with a series of earthquakes hitting a chain of small
islands off Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, a 6.4 magnitude earthquake rocked the island of
Kozushima, 93 miles southwest of Tokyo. A 34-year-old fisherman was
killed in a car buried under fallen rocks on the island.
</P>
<P>
   From Saturday through Thursday afternoon, nearly 9,000 tremors,
most of them too weak to be felt by humans, had been registered on
Kozushima and nearby small islands.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is one of the world's most earthquake-prone countries as
it sits atop four tectonic plates, slabs of land that move across
the earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Meteorological Agency: http://www.kishou.go.jp
</P>
</TEXT>
