<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Kirogi Heads For Japan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Typhoon Kirogi was moving north-northeast toward
Japan on Thursday afternoon after leaving at least 10 people dead
in the Philippines, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With sustained winds of 89 miles an hour near its center, Kirogi
was located as of noon about 400 miles east-southeast of Okinawa,
the Meteorological Agency said. Okinawa, the main island in Japan's
southernmost state, is about 1,000 miles southwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The typhoon was moving at a speed of 12 mph to the
north-northeast and was expected to affect coastal areas near Tokyo
by Saturday morning, weather forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Philippines, three more typhoon-related deaths were
reported Thursday, bringing the death toll there to ten,
authorities said. Kirogi and a tropical depression brought heavy
rains there earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   A mother and her daughter were killed early Thursday when their
house below a hill was hit by rock and mud slides in La Trinidad
town in the Philippines' northern Benguet Province. Another person
was killed after a wall collapsed in Cavite Province, south of
Manila, disaster management officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the weather had improved some in Manila, the government
still suspended all classes in the capital Thursday to allow
residents to recover from flood waters, which had begun to recede.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Meteorological Agency: http://www.kishou.go.jp
</P>
</TEXT>
