<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Off on Good Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Good growing weather depressed grain and soybean
prices Thursday in early dealings on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Slumping corn sank further after the National Weather Service
called for wet, cool conditions in mid-July. The short-term picture
already has showers coming to prime growing regions this week,
which boosts prospects for a record crop this year.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans also were pressured by the benign weather outlook for
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat's decline was only minimal, as Egypt's purchase of U.S.
wheat offset pressures from the harvest and from the drop in corn
and soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for September delivery fell &AMP;frac14; cent to $2.58&AMP;frac12; a bushel;
December corn fell 2&AMP;frac12; cents to $2.01&AMP;frac12; a bushel; September oats
fell
&AMP;frac12; cent to $1.01 a bushel; November soybeans fell 6 cents to $4.66 a
bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were mixed in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures were higher.
</P>
<P>
   August live cattle rose 1 cent to 67.82 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle fell .10 cent to 87.92 cents a pound; August lean
hogs rose .62 cent to 68.77 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose
1.10 cent to 87 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
