<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 39; Nasdaq Gains 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower Thursday as investors
remained worried about slumping corporate profits. Technology
issues, including the largest blue chips, led the decline.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 39.25 at 10,444.35.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower, having given up
earlier gains. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 0.80 at
1,445.43, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 1.96 at 3,865.06.
</P>
<P>
   With interest rates rising, investors have become worried that
corporate profits will suffer. In Wednesday's session, a flurry of
profit warnings sent technology stocks dramatically lower.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, technology stocks were regaining their balance, but
investors had turned negative toward blue-chips, particularly the
drug stocks that have performed well in recent weeks. Johnson &AMP;
Johnson was down $1.25 to $99.75 and Merck was down $1.563 at
$75.625.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it may be difficult for the market to advance
until companies begin reporting actual numbers later this month.
Even then, argued Charles Pradilla, chief investment strategist at
SG Cowen Securities, investors will apply fierce standards.
Technology stocks, which are still expensive relative to many
old-economy stocks, will face the toughest scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ''When an asset is expensive, very minor disappointments can
kill the stock,'' he said. ''With very high valuations, there's
very little room for error. They take them out and shoot them if
anything goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of high-profile technology stocks tumbled.
Hewlett-Packard fell $3.188 to $116.438, IBM fell $2.313 to
$101.438 and JDS Uniphase lost $6.375 to $112.625.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-8 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 419.15 million
shares, behind Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, breadth was much worse, with three stocks falling
for every two that rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 1.98 to 516.27.
</P>
<P>
