<HEADLINE> Dow Loses 25; Nasdaq Gains 37  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Thursday as investors remained
worried about slumping corporate profits. Technology issues showed
a dramatic rift, with blue-chip computer makers down and
semiconductor names improving.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 25.11 at 10,458.49.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators had turned higher, having recovered
from earlier losses. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 5.48 at
1,451.71, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 37.02 at 3,900.12.
</P>
<P>
   With interest rates rising, investors have become worried that
corporate profits will suffer. In Wednesday's session, a flurry of
profit warnings sent technology stocks dramatically lower.
</P>
<P>
   Some weakness persisted on Thursday. IBM fell for a fourth
straight session as investors worried that its second-quarter
results will miss expectations. Merrill Lynch analyst Steve
Milunovich fueled those fears with a research note indicating that
companies that do business with IBM are struggling, and may cut
back on orders.
</P>
<P>
   IBM fell $2.875 to $100.875.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, semiconductor stocks that tumbled on Wednesday staged
a modest recovery. LSI Logic was up $1.188 to $51.688.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had turned negative toward blue-chips, particularly
the drug stocks that have performed well in recent weeks. Johnson &AMP;
Johnson was down $1.50 to $99.50 and Merck was down $1.563 at
$75.625.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it may be difficult for the market to advance
until companies begin reporting actual numbers later this month.
Even then, argued Charles Pradilla, chief investment strategist at
SG Cowen Securities, investors will apply fierce standards.
Technology stocks, which are still expensive relative to many
old-economy stocks, will face the toughest scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ''When an asset is expensive, very minor disappointments can
kill the stock,'' he said. ''With very high valuations, there's
very little room for error. They take them out and shoot them if
anything goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM wasn't the only high-profile technology stock to tumble.
Hewlett-Packard fell $3.188 to $116.438 and JDS Uniphase lost
$5.188 to $113.813.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-8 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 628.99 million
shares, slightly ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, breadth was much worse, with three stocks falling
for every two that rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was unchanged at 518.25.
</P>
<P>
