<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Gunmen Kill 2, Surrender  </HEADLINE>
By SEAN YOONG
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAUK, Malaysia (AP) -- Anti-terrorist commandos converged on an
armed gang in Malaysia's dense northern jungle Thursday and forced
the Islamic militants to surrender, ending a four-day standoff in
which two hostages were slain.
</P>
<P>
   The surrender of the 27 militants, who had raided two military
armories, brought Malaysia's worst security crisis in years to an
uneasy close amid revelations that the gunmen repeatedly shot one
captive, an army ranger, in both legs before killing him.
</P>
<P>
   A police intelligence detective also was slain. Two other other
hostages, a farmer and a detective, were freed when the gunmen
surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the armed group said the hostages were killed in
retaliation for the wounding of gunmen in firefights. Five wounded
gunmen were among those who turned themselves in to police and
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The last holdouts reluctantly laid down their arms, which
included machetes, when confronted by the government commandos,
Defense Minister Najib Tun Razak said.
</P>
<P>
   The violence raised concerns about Islamic militancy in this
predominantly Muslim Southeast Asian country, which has little
experience with sectarian strife or terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The gang belong to a group called Al-Ma'unah, or Brotherhood of
Inner Power, and were led by a former army private, identified as
Amin Razali. He was the last to surrender, Najib said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They want to use violence and they want to create chaos,''
Najib said. ''They were carried away by this notion of an Islamic
state. The acts were criminal in nature. This is not the face of
Islam that we want to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Najib said that all the arms -- more than 100 assault rifles,
grenade launchers and light machine guns -- seized in the raids at
two camps on Sunday -- were recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Norian Mai, the national police chief, estimated that Al-Ma'unah
has a few hundred members.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Ma'unah grew out of an Indonesian martial arts group but now
had no links with overseas organizations or local political
parties, Norian said.
</P>
<P>
   Former soldiers are among its members, and three servicemen were
among the raiding band. But Norian said most of the raiders ''were
holding a gun for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kuala Lumpur, Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi
said some in the group were professionals, including engineers and
accountants.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have good jobs and good salaries,'' he said. ''I don't
know why they chose to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Ma'unah espouses holy war and promotes martial arts, the
group's Web site said, describing it as a non-governmental
organization formed in September 1998, when political turmoil
erupted in Malaysia after the sacking and arrest of Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   It claimed the group had 1,000 members in Malaysia, Brunei,
Singapore, Egypt and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Those who surrendered are in police custody in Sauk; 15 were
detained under the Internal Security Act.
</P>
<P>
   Under the act, dating from a communist insurgency in the 1950s,
simple possession of bullets is punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the gunmen would face the gallows, Najib said:
''They have committed murder. It all depends on the evidence we can
gather.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 1429 </TRAILER>
