<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 10; Nasdaq Adds 61  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mostly higher in volatile trading
Thursday as investors bought stocks that have fallen steeply in
recent sessions. Many investors remained worried about slumping
corporate profits, turning against blue-chip computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   With less than an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular
session, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 9.54 at 10,493.14.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators had turned higher, having recovered
from earlier losses. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.00
at 1,456.23, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 60.78 at
3,923.88.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks shook off early weakness as investors began bargain
hunting, snapping up shares of companies that have been battered in
recent sessions. Oracle rose $3.188 to $75.50.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, semiconductor stocks that tumbled on Wednesday staged
a modest recovery. LSI Logic was up $1.188 to $51.688.
</P>
<P>
   Also, energy stocks recovered after a number of analysts said a
selloff on Wednesday was overdone. The sector suffered after Saudi
Arabia said it would begin pumping an additional 500,000 barrels of
crude oil per day.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil rose $1.75 to $78.688.
</P>
<P>
   But concerns about corporate earnings lingered. With interest
rates rising, investors have become worried that corporate profits
will suffer, and in Wednesday's session, a flurry of profit
warnings sent technology stocks dramatically lower.
</P>
<P>
   Some weakness persisted on Thursday. IBM fell for a fourth
straight session as investors worried that its second-quarter
results will miss expectations. Merrill Lynch analyst Steve
Milunovich fueled those fears with a research note indicating that
companies that do business with IBM are struggling, and may cut
back on orders.
</P>
<P>
   IBM fell $2.188 to $101.563.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had turned negative toward blue-chips, particularly
the drug stocks that have performed well in recent weeks. Johnson &AMP;
Johnson was down $1.50 to $99.50 and Merck was down $1.563 at
$75.625.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it may be difficult for the market to advance
until companies begin reporting actual numbers later this month.
Even then, argued Charles Pradilla, chief investment strategist at
SG Cowen Securities, investors will apply fierce standards.
Technology stocks, which are still expensive relative to many
old-economy stocks, will face the toughest scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ''When an asset is expensive, very minor disappointments can
kill the stock,'' he said. ''With very high valuations, there's
very little room for error. They take them out and shoot them if
anything goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM wasn't the only high-profile technology stock to tumble.
Hewlett-Packard fell $3.188 to $116.438 and JDS Uniphase lost
$5.188 to $113.813.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-8 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 744.61 million
shares, slightly ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, breadth was much worse, with three stocks falling
for every two that rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up at 519.19.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
