<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Leaders Urge Concessions  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian leaders spent Thursday
lowering expectations for next week's Mideast summit near
Washington, each saying success depends on concessions by the
other.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton invited Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to the presidential resort at Camp
David on July 11 to try to work out a framework for a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides seem locked into their present positions by
internal problems, as public support for the two leaders fades.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said chances for success at the summit meeting are no more
than 50 percent, ''like the toss of a coin.'' Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat predicted a second summit would be needed,
with negotiations in between.
</P>
<P>
   The summit invitation set in motion a further splintering of
Barak's governing team. Opposing concessions to the Palestinians,
two of his six coalition parties moved toward the exit, just two
weeks after an internal crisis led to resignation of another
party's Cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showed Barak's popularity at a low point, and Arafat, the
only consensus leader the Palestinians have ever had, was also
suffering in public opinion surveys. Looking over their shoulders
at their domestic opposition, the two leaders would find it
difficult to compromise at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred Israeli settlers from the West Bank demonstrated
outside Barak's residence in Jerusalem, protesting his readiness to
give up significant parts of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are aiming for a target of Sept. 13 to complete a
peace treaty. Palestinians say they intend to declare an
independent state then, with or without a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Gaps are still wide. The Palestinians want a state in all the
West Bank and Gaza Strip with the Arab section of Jerusalem as its
capital. Israel is offering most of the West Bank but wants to keep
areas where most Israeli settlers live and insists on sovereignty
over all Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   There are also significant differences over Palestinian refugees
and over release of prisoners in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's military is preparing for violence in the West Bank,
according to a senior officer. Speaking on condition of anonymity,
he warned that Israel would use tanks, planes and helicopters
against Palestinian rioters if necessary. He said settlers are
getting riot control equipment, including rifles that fire
rubber-coated steel pellets.
</P>
<P>
   Members of parliament from the National Religious Party,
identified with Israeli settlers in the West Bank, voted Thursday
to quit Barak's government, a day after Israel B'Aliya,
representing immigrants from the former Soviet Union, announced it
would resign.
</P>
<P>
   In his first political speech since Barak trounced him in
elections in May 1999, former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
expressed support for the settlers and called for restraint on all
sides. ''This is a debate among brothers,'' he said, referring to
disagreements over Barak's peace policies. ''There must be no civil
war.'' Netanyahu spoke at the settlement of Ofra, celebrating 25
years since it was established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
