<HEADLINE> Thousands of Poles Pour Into Rome  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Poland's favorite son did not go home this
summer -- so his countrymen came to him.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 Poles poured into St. Peter's Square on
Thursday to attend a special Mass celebrated by Pope John Paul II
as part of the Vatican's millennium celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The pope was clearly moved as the crowd waved red and white
Polish flags and sang hymns celebrating Poland's long Roman
Catholic tradition.
</P>
<P>
   With Poland's top political leadership present, John Paul called
for measures to ease the economic pain caused by the country's
transition to a free market economy. Any economic reforms must be
just and benefit all Poles, ''especially the poorest,'' the pope
said.
</P>
<P>
   After Mass, he greeted Polish President Alexsander Kwasniewski,
Polish Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek and the leaders of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The first buses carrying pilgrims began arriving two hours
before the Mass, which started at 8 a.m. to keep the frail
80-year-old pope out of the 90-degree-plus midday heat. They
returned in the evening for a prayer service led by John Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pilgrims came from parishes throughout Poland, but
there were also groups of Polish extraction from the United States,
Ukraine and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many believers wanted to be here absolutely because, even if
they don't say it, they are thinking that this is the last chance
to see him,'' said Tadeusz Jarzab, 47, who came from a town near
Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   There had been talk of John returning to Poland this summer, but
Holy Year commitments have kept him in Rome. He leaves Sunday for a
13-day vacation in the Italian Alps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
