<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Reviews China Plan  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- World Bank directors reviewed a contentious
loan on Thursday that would resettle poor Chinese farmers to
traditionally Tibetan lands. The United States and environmental
and human rights groups oppose the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The board of directors choices were to go ahead with the $40
million project, cancel it, or carry out further environmental and
social studies over the next 15 to 18 months before providing any
funds, bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A decision was expected later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Bank President James Wolfensohn has recommended a delay but
China opposes consultants making extensive visits to the remote
western area. China has a seat on the 24-member bank board which
makes the final decision on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Some supporters of the resettlement plan argue that if China
agrees to make public the environmental and social assessments
conducted by international experts for the project, it would be
taking another step toward political liberalization.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the loan would be used to resettle 58,000
impoverished Chinese and Hui Muslim farmers in lands in Qinghai
Province that are the traditional homeland for 4,000 Tibetan and
Mongol herders.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Tibetan groups contend resettlement would aid China's effort
to dilute its minority Tibetan population. Tibet's exiled spiritual
leader, the Dalai Lama, said last month after a meeting with
President Clinton that the bank initiative ''would be a source of
more problems'' and should not proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Several protesters from the Campaign for Tibet camped out in
front of bank headquarters for the fourth day Thursday, calling for
cancellation of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups object to the part of the plan that would
underwrite construction of dams and irrigation canals in the
resettlement area.
</P>
<P>
   China insisted last week the project is supported by those who
would be relocated and by the Tibetans living in the province. The
Beijing government said the initiative would also raise living
standards and would strictly adhered to Chinese and World Bank
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Germany voted against the funding when it
first came before the board in June 1999. Some other nations
abstained.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the controversy, the directors earlier delayed
the loan until the bank's independent inspection panel, composed of
three development experts, could conduct a review.
</P>
<P>
   That panel found that the bank repeatedly violated its own rules
for protecting the environment and consulting those affected by the
project. The group said bank managers failed to consider
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's scathing report raised the larger issue of whether
the bank is sufficiently sensitive to the social and political
ramifications of its projects.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials also questioned the World Bank's evaluation of
the potential impact of an oil field and pipeline project in Chad
and Cameroon that was approved early in June, despite environmental
and congressional opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelossi, D-Calif, rounded up 59 other lawmakers to
sign a letter urging Wolfensohn to make the panel's report public.
He was ready to comply when the board, at the behest of China and
other borrowing countries, overruled him and held up publication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
