<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decision Near on Anthrax Vaccination  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With supplies of the anthrax vaccine
dwindling, Defense Secretary William Cohen is expected to decide
soon whether to suspend or slow the pace of soldier inoculations,
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A set of options is to be presented to Cohen by aides before he
departs Monday on a trip to China, said Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, a
Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we get his guidance, we will take that action and we will
announce his decisions,'' Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to discuss specific options, although other defense
officials said the options include suspending the vaccination
program. Some military members believe the government has failed to
demonstrate that the vaccine presents no substantial health risk.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely first step, some officials believe, would be to
slow the rate of inoculations to conserve supplies.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,500 doses are now administered daily. The Pentagon has
about 190,000 doses available for use, meaning that at the current
rate of inoculations it would run out in 42 days unless more
supplies are made available or Cohen orders a slowdown in
inoculations.
</P>
<P>
   A new batch of about 194,000 doses is being tested; if certified
for use, it would ease the supply crunch for at least another
month.
</P>
<P>
   A more lasting solution will come if the Food and Drug
Administration certifies the new manufacturing facility in Lansing,
Mich., of the country's lone anthrax vaccine producer, Bioport
Corp. Quigley said that might be ''many months'' away.
</P>
<P>
   Current supplies of the vaccine come from stockpiles produced by
a small laboratory attached to the University of Michigan, which
manufactured only small quantities of vaccine each year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, about 19 percent of the 2.4 million Defense Department
employees have been given at least one of the series of anthrax
vaccine shots that must be administered to achieve full protection
against the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax typically afflicts animals, especially sheep and cattle.
Dry anthrax spores, which can be put into weapons, can be fatal to
humans when inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon began the vaccination program in response to a
growing concern in the Clinton administration that North Korea,
Iraq or other nations hostile to the United States might launch an
anthrax attack on U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   Several House members have urged Cohen to stop the vaccinations
until the Pentagon finds an improved vaccine, and some soldiers
have refused vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Pentagon anthrax program: http://www.anthrax.osd.mil
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
