<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agency To Help Blind Test-Takers  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second time in less than a year, the
Justice Department has won agreement from a national agency that
tests social workers to provide qualified readers for blind or
vision-impaired test-takers.
</P>
<P>
   The department announced Thursday that it filed a lawsuit in
federal court in Des Moines, Iowa, alleging that the American
Association of State Social Work Boards violated the Americans with
Disabilities Act. At the same time, it filed a proposed court
order, based on its new agreement with the association, that would
resolve the lawsuit, if the court approves.
</P>
<P>
   This association of state bodies that regulate social work
offers a licensing examination used throughout the nation. The
agreement was seen by the government as a model for other national
testing agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the widespread use and importance of standardized
testing, it is vital that people who are blind be given a fair
opportunity to demonstrate their knowledge and ability,'' said
Acting Assistant Attorney General Bill Lann Lee of the department's
civil rights division. ''Companies that offer standardized tests
should follow this agreement so that the examinations they offer
truly test the aptitude and achievement levels of people with
disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Last September, the department reached an out-of-court
settlement on the same issues with the association and with
Assessment Systems Inc. (ASI), which previously worked with the
association in administering the test.
</P>
<P>
   But the department said it received indications the association
was not complying with the out-of-court agreement, so it filed the
lawsuit and a new agreement to settle it.
</P>
<P>
   A court-approved settlement is easier to police than an
out-of-court settlement, because any failure to comply becomes a
violation of a court order. The government can haul suspected
violators back before the court and demand they show cause why they
should not be held in contempt. At that time, the burden of proof
is on the alleged violator, not the government.
</P>
<P>
   ASI complied fully with the earlier agreement by adopting new
policies, training more than 200 employees and informing dozens of
testing agencies of those policies, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   The original investigation was triggered by a complaint from
Douglas Elliott, who was blinded in Vietnam but had been a social
worker for more than 20 years. When Elliott moved to Iowa, he had
to pass the exam to be certified there. Examination officials told
him he could not provide his own reader; instead, they assigned
one.
</P>
<P>
   The reader allegedly had never before read for a person with
impaired vision and had great difficulty. The government's
complaint alleges that the reader stumbled over technical terms,
made mistakes in recording Elliott's answers and became exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   A department official, requesting anonymity, said the case was
reopened when the association failed to pay Elliott $1,500 in
agreed upon damages and told its members that the September
agreement did not require anything not done before.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement requires the association to adopt written
policies ensuring that readers are proficient in working with the
blind, familiar with the test and have worked with the particular
test-taker before the exam. The association will pay for the reader
and test-taker to become familiar with each other.
</P>
<P>
   While denying it violated the disabilities act, the association
also agreed to:
</P>
<P>
   --Name an ADA coordinator to answer inquiries from disabled
people who want to take the test.
</P>
<P>
   --Train all employees and publicize the new policies so
test-takers know their options, including supplying their own
readers.
</P>
<P>
   --Pay Elliott $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department ADA site:
http://www.usdoj.gov/crt/ada/adahom1.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
