<HEADLINE> Russians Brace for Chechen Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- A top Chechen rebel commander said in a
video released Thursday that his forces were thriving despite
Russian claims of impending victory, while Russian officials took
stock of recent military losses.
</P>
<P>
   In the video, filmed Wednesday by Associated Press Television
News, a rebel group pitched camp under cover of a lush green
forest, joked, smiled and fingered an arsenal of machine guns,
assault rifles and rocket propelled grenades.
</P>
<P>
   At least scores of fighters, many appearing tanned and healthy,
carried hiking backpacks and led horses laden with stocks of food
and ammunition. They cheered and saluted the camera.
</P>
<P>
   The video demonstrated that the rebels can muster a large force
despite Russian claims to have dispersed the guerrilla bands into
groups no larger than 10 or 15 people. It showed the rebels
apparently at ease, despite the massive Russian military presence
nearby the rebel camp, located in the foothills of the Caucasus
Mountains near the town of Bamut.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russian officials have announced worldwide that the war is
over,'' said the group's leader, prominent commander Khamzat
Gilayev said. ''We also think that their war is over. We are
starting our own war, that is my understanding of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilayev was apparently referring to recent bombings and surprise
attacks launched by rebels on Russian positions. In the most deadly
attack, suicide truck bombs killed 33 and wounded 84 soldiers in
five coordinated attacks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials on Thursday traded blame for the bombings and
laid plans to prevent further losses -- but dismissed the idea of a
rebel comeback, and said they still control the rebel republic.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov met Thursday with the pro-Moscow
civilian leader in Chechnya, Akhmed Kadyrov, to discuss economic
revival.
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov said lifting the region out of poverty is necessary to
discourage armed resistance, and said his homeland is owed about
$53 million in back pension payments, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin huddled with top military commanders in
the Kremlin to discuss boosting law enforcement in Chechnya, news
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy chief of the general staff Gen. Valery Manilov said
Thursday the bombings will not mark a turning point in the war.
''There's no basis to talk of the collapse of the counter-terrorist
operation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Manilov said most of the republic is governable. He said the
rebels' the majority of important leaders are confined in a
mountain area less than 18 miles wide and 54 miles long. Attack
jets and artillery pounded the area Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said most of the estimated 1,500 to 2,000 rebels are also in
this area, although the band filmed by APTN was well to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Last week 61 Russian soldiers died and 153 were wounded in
Chechnya, Manilov said. He declined to give an updated total for
the war. The official figure has surpassed 2,000, though critics
estimate it is much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya by independence
fighters in a 1994-96 war. They returned in September, after
Islamic militants based there raided villages in neighboring
Dagestan, and after 300 people died in apartment bombings the
government blames on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 1701 </TRAILER>
