<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall complains of hospital-driven SUNY shortfall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A shortfall at the State University of New
York's three hospitals caused the system to end its fiscal year
$114 million in debt, and to borrow from the state to make up the
shortfall, New York's comptroller complained Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   H. Carl McCall said it is the second year SUNY has had to take a
short-term loan from the state until it could replace the money
with its own revenues from the new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the system had to borrow $77 million. McCall said
SUNY's fiscal plan already calls for the need to get another loan,
for $207 million, in June 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're actually planning a year in advance to continue to
ignore the problem,'' McCall grumbled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY's fiscal year runs from July 1 to June 30.
</P>
<P>
   McCall faulted SUNY administrators, Gov. George Pataki and the
state Legislature for failing to address the SUNY hospital
shortfall in the 2000-01 state budget which was enacted in May.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said it is no secret that the hospitals have been in
financial trouble and to ''sweep it under the rug'' is becoming
more and more impractical as the shortfall mount.
</P>
<P>
   A report prepared for SUNY trustees by PricewaterhouseCoopers
concluded earlier this year that the hospitals are operated
efficiently. But the consultants said the health centers will not
make any money if the state continues to require that they send
money to the rest of the SUNY system.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY's hospitals are in Syracuse, Brooklyn and Stony Brook.
</P>
<P>
   A SUNY spokesman had no immediate comment on McCall's
complaints.
</P>
</TEXT>
