<HEADLINE> Teen to be tried as adult in alleged plot to burn parents, brother  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - A Trumbull teen-ager will be tried as
an adult for allegedly plotting to kill her father, mother and
brother by setting fire to the family home while they slept.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Neville, 15, burst into tears Thursday when Superior
Court Judge Burton Kaplan ruled she was to face three counts of
attempted murder and one count of arson.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that shortly after 3 a.m. on June 2 the girl
splashed gasoline around the inside of her family's home, including
soaking some clothing outside the bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   When firefighters arrived at the home they found the girl's
father, Gary Neville, had managed to put out the fire, which he
said had sent flames up to 3 feet high outside the bedroom. Neville
was treated for smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, firefighters found a line of
gasoline-soaked clothing in front of the bedrooms on the second
floor of the raised ranch house. The piles of clothes culminated in
a 1-gallon container of gasoline outside the brother's door.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the fire caused $30,000 in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Neville, who denies setting the fire, said she leaped
from her window to escape the flames.
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived, they found the girl crying and limping as
she stood outside her home. She said she had injured her leg when
she leapt from her bedroom window. But police said an examination
at the hospital found no signs of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Following an investigation, police arrested Neville on June 26.
She was released on a promise to appear in court, which remains in
effect until her next hearing. Until then, she must adhere to a
9:30 p.m. curfew and wear an electronic monitoring anklet.
</P>
<P>
   The girl left the courthouse with family members, including her
father, brother and an aunt. Her case was continued until July 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
