<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Clears Plans for Peace Talk  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's
spokesman assured Japan on Thursday she was skipping a high-level
conference next week in Miyazaki only because of the urgency of
Mideast summit talks at Camp David, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Albright explained to Foreign Minister Yohei Kono in a half-hour
telephone call why she would not attend the foreign ministers
meeting and he ''expressed his understanding of the critical timing
of the Middle East peace talks,'' spokesman Richard Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of Britain, Canada, France, Germany,
Italy, Japan and Russia are due to meet at Miyazaki next Wednesday
and Thursday to prepare for a Group of Eight summit meeting on
Okinawa July 21-23.
</P>
<P>
   The Camp David summit opens next Tuesday, and Albright will
participate along with President Clinton and other U.S. officials.
She is sending Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott to Japan in
her place.
</P>
<P>
   The city responded by deciding not to name a 500-seat auditorium
in its new civic center after Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ''Miyazaki's junior high school students and other citizens
looked forward to the visit,'' Miyazaki City Mayor Shigemitsu
Tsumura said. ''We think this is very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said Albright regretted she could not attend the foreign
ministers meeting and speak at the civic center
</P>
<P>
   ''The Middle East peace process is at a critical juncture, and
the summit offers a real change for a historic agreement,'' the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said Albright would visit Japan later on. ''They are
strong allies and friends,'' he said of the Japanese. ''We
certainly look forward to doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no word on whether Clinton would cancel his attendance
at the G-8 summit if Mideast peace talks were still in progress.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he voiced hope for an accord within a few days,
but said there were no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are due here this weekend
for pre-summit talks on Sunday and Monday. Boucher said Albright
would meet with them.
</P>
<P>
   The summit itself will be held in seclusion. Boucher said
Thursday that briefings for the news media will be held at a press
center yet to be selected.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't expect to get any complete and full daily readout
of the issues under discussion,'' Boucher advised reporters at the
State Department. ''We will try to make available what information
we can, but I don't want anybody to anticipate enormous amounts of
information at those briefings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
