<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SUNY chancellor to have heart bypass surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Robert King, chancellor of the State
University of New York system, will have elective heart bypass
surgery Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A brief statement from SUNY's central administrative office in
Albany Thursday announced King's impending surgery and promised
further updates ''as appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The chancellor is expected to be able to resume some of his
duties within a month's time and the nature of his condition
indicates that he can expect a full and complete recovery,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY spokesman Dave Henahan could not say where the surgery was
to be performed or if King has a history of heart problems
personally or in his family.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old King has been chancellor since December. He
previously was the first director of the Governor's Office of
Regulatory Reform and state budget director in the Pataki
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, King was a Republican state assemblyman - serving
with George Pataki in that chamber - and Monroe County executive.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who is close to King, issued a statement Thursday
praising King for proving himself ''a dynamic leader committed to
making SUNY, already the finest university system in America, even
better.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My best thoughts and prayers are with my friend, who I am
confident will have a full recovery,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   While King convalesces, his duties at SUNY will be handled by
Provost Peter Salins, Vice Chancellor Richard Miller and Vice
Chancellor John O'Connor, depending on the subject matter, Henahan
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
