<HEADLINE> Tipper Gore raises money for DNC, tours youth program  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Tipper Gore was all smiles as children
crowded around her Thursday to tell of their adventures in a summer
program that teaches leadership and confidence by dangling them
from ropes 30 feet up in the treetops.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not scary,'' one student told the wife of the Democratic
presidential candidate during a stop at Hartford's Riverside Park.
</P>
<P>
   ''Are we on TV?'' another asked as cameras pressed around them.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of scary,'' a girl said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore chimed in: ''I'm really impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one kid asked the money question: ''Who's ahead in the
polls?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore laughed and responded the polls are about even.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Edward Rendell, chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, urged supporters at two fund-raisers to sign their
friends up for the Democratic cause this election. They urged
people to pitch in with support from their pocketbooks and elbow
grease to help Vice President Al Gore beat Texas Gov. George W.
Bush in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need your resources. Thank you for coming,'' Rendell told
about 120 people who paid $50 apiece for a stand-up reception where
they munched on bagel chips, feta cheese and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   At a $500-a-plate lunch of grilled chicken, salad and
cheesecake, Gore said her husband would expand on President
Clinton's economic successes and uphold traditional party stands on
civil rights, education and support for working families.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to continue to widen the circle of opportunity,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raisers at The Hartford Club were expected to raise
about $100,000 for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   People who attended the event included top Democrats in the
Connecticut party, lobbyists, town party leaders and interested
party members.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Wolfe, of Simsbury, came to the reception after she got
a letter in the mail notifying her about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never given $50 to a candidate before in my life, but I
feel so strongly for the issues she stands for, especially
environmental issues, and Tipper's been such a leader on mental
health issues,'' Wolfe said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to meeting with campers at Riverside Park, Gore
visited the summer job and recreation programs offered by
Riverfront Recapture, a group that is restoring the city's access
to the Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   She watched teen-agers plane wood to make a boat, and others who
rowed a boat out into the river. The youngsters on the ropes course
in the woods crowded around her to tell of their achievements
</P>
<P>
   ''This gives a kid a sense of accomplishment, I think,'' Gore
said, adding that she thinks the program should be expanded to
other cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
