<HEADLINE> American Express chairman denies fee scheme  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Taking the witness stand Thursday at an
antitrust trial, an American Express Co. official fended off
suggestions that his company plotted to promote inflated credit
card fees at the expense of the average consumer.
</P>
<P>
   American Express chairman Harvey Golub conceded that billions of
dollars are at stake over the rates merchants are charged when a
customer uses a credit card - costs often passed on to consumers.
But he denied trying to lure banks away from Visa and MasterCard
and into deals with American Express so that the banks would adopt
higher rates charged by his company.
</P>
<P>
   During cross-examination, Visa's attorney pushed Golub about a
speech he made in 1996 to a credit card conference. Golub at the
time attacked the credit card associations' rules that prevent
member banks from issuing cards other than Visa and MasterCard and
urged that the banks seek ''terms that would also allow you to work
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Golub said he was looking out for the ''best interest'' of both
the banks and their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''And I would define that interest as doing business with us,''
he said before concluding two days of testimony at the trial in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department contends in its antitrust suit against
Visa USA Inc., Visa International and MasterCard International Ltd.
that the card companies violated antitrust law by limiting
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that the same group of banks control both Visa
and MasterCard, thwarting competition between the two networks. It
also accuses the card companies of adopting rules designed to
discourage banks from doing business with American Express, Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.'s Discover card and others.
</P>
<P>
   Visa and MasterCard have denied the allegations. They have
accused American Express of lobbying federal authorities into suing
Visa and MasterCard as part of a ''trench warfare'' battle plan.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued after Golub's testimony, Kelly Presta,
Visa's vice president for public affairs, said that banks,
retailers and consumers ''are too smart'' to fall for American
Express' arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ''They know the real story, even if Harvey Golub continues to
deny the real cause of his company's problems: high-priced products
and even higher merchant fees,'' Presta said.
</P>
<P>
   Visa and MasterCard also claim American Express has sought to
''cherry pick'' their biggest and best bank customers at the
expense of consumers. In testimony on Wednesday, Golub said
American Express would like to partner with many banks in the
United States, not just the largest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-06-00 1741 </TRAILER>
