<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Steps Up Border Security  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE BOEHMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Germany will reimpose controls along
its borders to screen out members of Iranian opposition groups who
may try to disrupt next week's visit by Iranian President Mohammed
Khatami, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry said it has received ''serious tips'' that
Iranian opposition groups, including some based outside Germany,
are planning disturbances during Khatami's visit on July 10-12 --
the first by an Iranian leader to Germany since Iran's 1979 Islamic
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary border controls, which begin Friday, will include
passport checks. A 1995 agreement by Germany and eight other
European Union nations allows citizens to travel freely across
their borders without passports, but controls can be restored in
special circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also reportedly have placed travel restrictions on
Iranian exiles living in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   A German newspaper reported that security concerns are also
prompting Iran to reconsider the trip. In a report to appear
Friday, the Die Welt newspaper cited German officials as saying
they were uncertain if the visit would even take place after
security issues were repeatedly raised by an Iranian delegation in
Berlin ahead of the president's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami apparently fears that protests during the visit may
endanger his political position at home, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   A group of German writers appealed Thursday to Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder to bring up imprisonment and harassment of
Iranian writers and journalists in his talks with Khatami. In a
letter, the PEN writers club said that even though Iran had signed
the U.N. Human Rights Charter, intellectuals in the country are
imprisoned for expressing their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   A senior lawmaker from Schroeder's Social Democrats, Gernot
Erler, said the visit was meant to support Khatami's ''opening and
reform process'' in Iran, adding that ''alarming human rights
situation'' in Iran would ''of course'' also be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, a moderate cleric elected in 1997, is seeking to revive
contacts with Western Europe. Relations with Germany were frozen
after a German court in 1997 ruled that the 1992 shooting death of
four Iranian dissidents in Berlin had been ordered at the highest
level in Tehran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
