<HEADLINE> Second suspect pleads to helping torture disabled man  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) - A second man involved in the torture of a
learning-disabled person at a party faces up to 10 years in prison
as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Vistad, 24, of Middletown, pleaded guilty to conspiracy
and bias assault Wednesday in the Jan. 30, 1999, attack on Eric
Krochmaluk, 24, of Middletown.
</P>
<P>
   Eight people are charged in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Krochmaluk was bound to a chair and forced to perform several
embarrassing acts. Vistad and eight others allegedly shaved his
eyebrows, burned him with cigarettes, choked and beat him and
abandoned him in a forest. He was forced to kiss people's feet and
drink urine and warned that if he told police about the incident,
his parents' home would be burned down.
</P>
<P>
   Vistad, a former classmate of the victim's, said Wednesday he
and co-defendant William MacKay, 23, of Hazlet, plotted the attack
at a party at the home of two of the other suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we came out, (the victim) was surprised to see us,''
Vistad said. Krochmaluk ''was given iced tea with (the liquor)
Everclear and told to drink it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Vistad said, he left the room and returned to find
Krochmaluk had been dressed in women's clothes and had had his head
shaved.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea agreement, Assistant Monmouth County Prosecutor
Jacquelynn Seely agreed not to seek a more severe sentence under
state bias crime statutes, which carry penalties of up to 20 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay pleaded guilty to the same charges. Both MacKay and
Vistad will be sentenced in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
