<HEADLINE> Shape up or go hungry: Ferry's food operation cited as unsanitary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAPE MAY, N.J. (AP) - The operators of the Cape May-Lewes Ferry
have been given 30 days to fix ''very significant unsanitary
conditions'' in the food operations on two of their ships.
</P>
<P>
   The violations were spotted during routine inspections of the MV
Twin Capes and the MV Cape May by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration. They included unsanitary employee food handling,
equipment problems and the serving of undercooked hot dogs and
coffee creamers that weren't adequately chilled.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have complaints of illness, but the potential was
there,'' said Ray Abrahams, director of compliance for the FDA's
office in Parsippany.
</P>
<P>
   He called the problems ''very significant unsanitary
conditions'' and placed the Delaware River and Bay Authority, which
operates the ferry service between New Jersey and Delaware, on
''provisional status.'' The ships can continue to serve food in the
meantime.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's our goal to not only meet the expectations, but to exceed
the FDA regulations,'' said James Salmon, a spokesman for the
authority. ''(DRBA chief operating officer Jeff Lewis) has taken
immediate action on equipment, training, the warehouse operation
and cleanliness issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
