<DOCNO> APW20000706.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Connecticut Baseball Hall of Fame proposed for Bridgeport  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - Local leaders are trying to build a
Connecticut Baseball Hall of Fame and museum, using the
19th-century Bridgeport home of James O'Rourke, a member of the
National Baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   City officials recently agreed to sell the Queen Anne style home
for $1 to Michael Hoffman, a magazine publisher from Bridgeport who
hopes to raise up to $5 million to build the museum. The 1891 house
had been slated for demolition to make way for a retail project at
Steel Point, an old industrial site.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said the Hall of Fame and museum would be devoted to
honoring Connecticut's contribution to professional baseball - both
major and minor league players and teams.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the museum would be the home of O'Rourke, who
was elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame in 1945. O'Rourke
began his professional baseball career in 1872, helping the Boston
Red Stockings and Red Caps to five pennants. In 1884, he captured
the National League batting title with a .350 average. He was
nicknamed ''The Orator'' because he attended Yale Law School.
O'Rourke died in Bridgeport in 1919.
</P>
<P>
   Other honorees would include National Hall of Famers Roger
Connor and Ned Hanlon.
</P>
<P>
   Connor, a Waterbury native, played for 18 seasons in the 1800s
and held the career home run record of 136 until Babe Ruth came
along in 1921 and hit 137 on his way to a career record of 714.
</P>
<P>
   Hanlon, from Montville, was a major-league manager for 19 years,
best-known for taking the last-place 1892 Baltimore Orioles to the
pennant in 1894.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is now negotiating with the city to buy a piece of land
on which to move the house and build the museum.
</P>
<P>
   One of the stipulations of the city's agreement to sell
O'Rourke's home for $1 is that the home remain in Bridgeport and be
used for the baseball museum.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once the (O'Rourke) house is moved and we get a chance to look
at the plan they submitted ... then we can continue the
negotiations,'' said Joe Gresko, a spokesman for Mayor Joseph P.
Ganim.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said he first got the idea when he was doing the
play-by-play for an exhibition baseball game in Bridgeport last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was saying to anyone who would listen to me, 'Why don't we
have a baseball museum?' '' said Hoffman, who said he has loved the
game since he played as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when he learned that the O'Rourke house was slated
for demolition, he asked the city to sell it to a new company he
formed, Connecticut Baseball Hall of Fame &AMP; Museum Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said he hopes to use the house itself as a base for the
museum, then do a major addition with a scaled-down version of a
professional baseball stadium. He hopes to include baseball
memorabilia, art galleries, lecture halls and an interactive
exhibit where visitors can pitch against Hall of Famers such as
Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman estimates the project will cost $5 million or more to
build and take five to seven years to complete. But he says he
believes the museum could become a hot tourist destination, citing
the current popularity of the city's minor league team, the
Bridgeport Bluefish.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have not found anyone who is not supportive of this
venture,'' Hoffman said. ''Everyone is quite excited about it, and
this is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, who publishes Sound People, a magazine that celebrates
Long Island Sound, said he is looking for financial backing for the
project from the city and state, and from corporations and private
donors.
</P>
<P>
   Gresko said officials have not decided yet whether the city will
support the project financially.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
