<HEADLINE> U.S. Closing Poland Aid Mission  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Calling Poland a success story, the United
States has decided to shut down its assistance program there after
11 years, the State Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Brady Anderson, the administrator of the U.S. Agency for
International Development, will travel to Poland next week to
officiate at a ceremony marking the end of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''Closing this mission in Warsaw marks the successful end to
U.S. foreign aid programs in Poland,'' State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And we always consider it a success when we can help out and
support people in their development needs but then see them reach a
stage of development where that kind of mission is no longer
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said the assistance program cost $19.1 million in fiscal
1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
