<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Seeking $40B in Aid  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The Palestinians are asking for $40 billion in
international aid to set up independent state once a peace
agreement with Israel is completed, Yasser Arafat's top economic
adviser said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Khaled Salam said the aid would be needed for Palestinian
refugees, infrastructure, budget expenditures and an early
retirement fund. Salam, also known as Mohammed Rashid, said Israel
would not be expected to come up with most of the money, but
''Israel should feel and take great responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is hosting a summit with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Arafat at Camp David on July 11 to try to
work out a framework for a peace treaty. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will also participate along with other U.S.
officials.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides seem locked into their present positions by
internal problems, as public support for the two leaders fades.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said chances for success at the summit meeting are no more
than 50 percent, ''like the toss of a coin.'' Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat predicted a second summit would be needed,
with negotiations in between.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showed Barak's popularity at a low point, and Arafat, the
only consensus leader the Palestinians have ever had, was also
suffering in public opinion surveys. Looking over their shoulders
at their domestic opposition, the two leaders would find it
difficult to compromise at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred Israeli settlers from the West Bank demonstrated
outside Barak's residence in Jerusalem, protesting his readiness to
give up significant parts of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are aiming for a target of Sept. 13 to complete a
peace treaty. Palestinians say they intend to declare an
independent state then, with or without a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Gaps are still wide. The Palestinians want a state in all of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip with the Arab section of Jerusalem as its
capital. Israel is offering most of the West Bank, but wants to
keep areas where most Israeli settlers live and insists on
sovereignty over all of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Salam, a member of the team that is to head to Camp David, said
the main problem is that Israel thinks in terms of ''what can I
give you.'' He said that the West Bank and Gaza belong to the
Palestinians, according to United Nations resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   However, he sounded a conciliatory note, saying the Palestinians
understand that Barak has some constraints in reaching a deal he
can sell to the Israeli public. ''The PLO and the Palestinian
delegation is seriously willing to have maximum flexibility in
dealing with Israeli needs,'' he told reporters in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's military is preparing for violence in the West Bank,
according to a senior officer. Speaking on condition of anonymity,
he warned that Israel would use tanks, planes and helicopters
against Palestinian rioters if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In his first political speech since Barak trounced him in
elections in May 1999, former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
expressed support for the settlers and called for restraint on all
sides. ''This is a debate among brothers,'' he said, referring to
disagreements over Barak's peace policies, adding, ''There must be
no civil war.'' Netanyahu spoke at the settlement of Ofra,
celebrating 25 years since it was established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
