<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that ing substantially or traded heavily
Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Qwest Communications Intl., down $2.375 at $54.813
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Joseph Nacchio told Dow Jones Newswires that rumors
that the company would buy WorldCom Inc. are ''premature and
ill-guided.'' Qwest just completed its merger with U S West after
49 weeks of sometimes contentious negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Federated Department Stores Inc., down $5.188 at $29.625
</P>
<P>
   The company said it is concerned about a rise in credit
delinquencies at its Fingerhut direct marketing unit in June.
Federated also reported a 0.5 percent same-store sales increase for
June, just slightly below analysts' predictions.
</P>
<P>
Sealed Air Corp., down $7.465 at $46.66
</P>
<P>
   The company said second-quarter earnings will miss expectations
due to sharp increases in the costs of certain resins used to
produce its packaging products. Sealed Air said resins costs rose
25 percent from the year-ago second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch Co., up $2.563 to $14.188
</P>
<P>
   Same-store sales for the month of June fell 4 percent, but total
sales for the month rose 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Visual Networks Inc., down $14.25 at $12
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to report earnings of 1 cent per share for
the second quarter, below analysts' expectations of 6 cents per
share. In addition, Visual Networks expects earnings and revenue
for the second half of 2000 and for 2001 to be below estimates.
Visual Networks provides network infrastructure for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Wavecom SA, up $20.25 at $129.25
</P>
<P>
   The company won a contract to supply Alcatel SA with digital
wireless technology for use in compact mobile phones by 2001.
Wavecom designs and makes fully integrated plug-in modules and
modems.
</P>
<P>
Intelligroup Inc., down $9.50 at $4.625
</P>
<P>
   The company has completed the spinoff of its Internet
professional services business, SeraNova Inc. The spinoff was
intended to allow Intelligroup to focus on its business as an
applications service provider.
</P>
</TEXT>
