<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court says it will hear police killer's parole case  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Convicted police killer Thomas Trantino
will remain in prison at least until Sept. 25, the date the state
Supreme Court is set to hear arguments on a judge's order to parole
him.
</P>
<P>
   The court said Thursday it will consider an appeal by Attorney
General John J. Farmer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The one-page order signed by Associate Justice Gary S. Stein
offered no reason why the court decided to take the case. It also
gave no details as to any vote by the justices.
</P>
<P>
   The court agreed June 16 that the lower-court order sending
Trantino to a halfway house to prepare him for release would be on
hold while an appeal is considered.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am pleased that the state Supreme Court, recognizing the
gravity of this matter, has granted the state's petition for
certification,'' Farmer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I continue to believe that the decision of the state Parole
Board, which was rendered after careful review and evaluation of
Mr. Trantino's record as an inmate, was correct,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino's lawyer, Roger Lowenstein, did not immediately return
calls Thursday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. Christie Whitman, who ordered Farmer to
pursue the appeal, would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's directive came after a decision published June 9
by a three-judge appeals panel. The panel said Trantino's latest
parole hearing was faulty and he deserved to be released after 37
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino, who was convicted of killing two Lodi police officers
in 1963, was denied parole at least nine times during his 37 years
behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel said in a 66-page opinion that Trantino's
latest rejection by the state parole board was ''not supported by
any credible evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Trantino was sentenced to die for killing officers Gary Tedesco
and Peter Voto in a bar in August 1963. But when New Jersey's death
penalty was overturned in 1972, Trantino's sentence was changed to
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing guidelines in effect at the time made Trantino
eligible for parole in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   After an earlier appeal, Trantino earned another chance at
release and a hearing before the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   At a June 1999 session, the board rejected Trantino's plea for
parole. Board members relied on a number of points, including
claims by prison mental health examiners that he would likely
commit another crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Trantino argued on appeal that parole board members ignored
several key points on his behalf. Trantino cited a prison record
that showed no infractions since 1970 and a report from a private
doctor and other tests that said he appeared to be a good candidate
for parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-06-00 1853 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
