<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Lazio should rename bus ''Double-Talk Express  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSON CITY, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton on Thursday
charged that her Republican Senate rival, Rep. Rick Lazio, was
engaging in ''personal insults'' and should rename his ''Mainstream
Express'' campaign bus, the ''Double-Talk Express.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard for me to get this straight. I mean, last week, he
was telling New Yorkers he wasn't responsible for his voting record
and this week he's telling us that he's not responsible for his
fund-raising letters,'' the first lady told reporters after a town
hall-style meeting at a Lockheed Martin plant near Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of the 'Mainstream Express,' he ought to call it the
'Double-Talk Express,''' she said. ''He's got moderate talk on the
campaign trail and extreme rhetoric in his (fund-raising) mail.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue was a direct mail fund-raising appeal that came to
light Wednesday in which Lazio told potential donors that ''Hillary
Clinton and her husband have embarrassed our country and disgraced
their powerful posts.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday about that language, the first lady said, ''I'm
just not going to respond to his personal insults. I'm just going
to run a campaign on issues, not insults, as I've tried to do now
for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Peppered by reporters for a second day with questions about his
fund-raising letter, Lazio said he had still not had a chance to
read it even though it had gone out over his signature. He also
continued to brush off its significance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand that there are many people that want to create a
smokescreen, try and divert attention from the true facts, which is
that I have a legislative record of serving the people of New York,
that we need to try and try very hard to communicate that record to
the people of New York and we're going to try and do that,'' the
congressman said during the fourth day of a five-day bus trip
across upstate New York, a key battleground in New York's U.S.
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without getting into an argument with you, the real question
is why has my opponent done six television commercials attacking me
and trying to distort my record?'' Lazio added. ''I have not had
any television commercials attacking her or distorting her record.
But she has chosen to go negative and to stay negative during this
campaign. I am trying very hard to talk about the issues that I
think New Yorkers care about.''
</P>
<P>
   During her more than one-hour meeting with employees of the
Lockheed Martin plant, Clinton was asked about the negative tenor
of American political campaigns. She used the opportunity to decry
that and to argue that she wasn't engaging in negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't called him any names. I will never call him names,''
Clinton said. ''As far as I know, he's nice person ... But I want
you to know where he stands on issues and where I stand on
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange came as Clinton kicked off her own five-day swing
across upstate New York, a sort of anniversary tour of the trip she
took across the state last July after visiting the farm of Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan to officially begin her Senate campaign.
Democrat Moynihan is retiring at the end of this year. It is his
Senate seat that Clinton and Lazio are fighting over.
</P>
<P>
   During her news conference Thursday, Clinton also faced
questions about her support for the death penalty. While saying she
remained a death penalty supporter, the first lady also said that
''in many states today it is being asked for much too often.'' She
also said that too often mistakes were being made that led to
improper convictions and death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd better do a better job than we're doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a Democratic picnic in Endicott, Clinton told more
than 1,100 enthusiastic Democrats, ''some people say I have an
agenda. Well, I do have an agenda ... I have an agenda to keep our
national economic prosperity going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
