<HEADLINE> Cyclist Crash Hurts Olympic Chances  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- Cyclist Johnny Bairos of
Redlands, Calif., is recovering after a serious crash during a
World Cup race, a mishap that may jeopardize his Olympic prospects.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Cycling is scheduled to announce the men's and women's
track teams for the Sydney Olympics on Friday, and it's unclear
whether Bairos can race again by September.
</P>
<P>
   Bairos, 22, was hurt while competing in match sprint at a World
Cup event June 18 in Mexico City. Racing against three others, he
was pushed off the track and fell more than 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Bairos broke his jaw in two places, broke his right kneecap and
bruised his right thigh. He also shattered his right sinus cavity
and fractured the left sinus cavity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember going over the railing and then the next thing I
remember was waking up in the ambulance,'' Bairos said. ''People
were telling me that I was lucky to be alive after the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Bairos is on U.S. Cycling's long team, a pool of elite riders
eligible for the Olympic squad. On Thursday, team officials were
culling the list to 11 men and three women.
</P>
<P>
   Bairos is one of the top American sprinters. He rode on the
three-man U.S. squad that won the gold medal in Olympic sprint at
last year's Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   He had surgery in Mexico and, after returning to California,
underwent additional surgery to insert two screws in his kneecap.
His training since then has been limited to riding a stationary
bike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
