<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court write-in election ruling not as expensive as first feared  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey counties will have to provide
more detailed instructions on how voters can cast write-in votes,
but won't have to invest millions of dollars in new voting machines
as a result of a recent state Supreme Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Two lawyers who represented parties in the case, in which
write-in candidates for local office in the Camden County town of
Chesilhurst won a second bite at the apple, said the ruling will
not take a huge bite out of county election budgets as first
feared.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the justices ordered only that counties prepare and post
instructions on how voters can cast tallies for write-in
candidates, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a much smaller impact now than what it could have been,''
said lawyer David Mapp, who represented the borough in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The trial court judge, in siding with the losing write-in
candidates' call for a new tally, ordered Camden County to purchase
new modern voting machines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That would have cost $6 million alone in the county, and untold
millions statewide, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court agreed with the trial judge - to a point.
Confusing write-in instructions cast doubt on the Chesilhurst
result, and the election ought to be redone, the justices said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the Supreme Court said only that the write-in instructions
were inadequate, that all we need to change is the instructions.
It's a great savings monetarily to taxpayers statewide,'' Mapp
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chesilhurst voters were confused about how to write in
votes in the November 1999 borough election, according to the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent Democratic Mayor Arland Poindexter went on to win the
election, but only by a 20-vote margin in a race in which 342 votes
were cast. He bested write-in candidate Kati Gray-Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, two incumbent councilmen defeated two write-in
hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   However, some write-in votes were ruled invalid because the
voters wrote the candidates' name on the wrong line. Others were
not counted when voters used stickers with the candidates' names on
them that the voting machines evidently stripped off.
</P>
<P>
   Gray-Sadler and her running mates filed a lawsuit complaining
they were denied a fair chance.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's decision, the court ordered counties to include
more detailed write-in instructions on sample ballots and at
polling places to prevent another botched election.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John Kearney, who represented the mayor, said the
ruling complicates election law. On one hand, it lowers the bar to
allow voter confusion to overturn election results. On the other,
it orders counties to limit voter confusion by providing more
precise instructions to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It adds a degree of uncertainty. Will the court be satisfied
with the new instructions?'' Kearney asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-06-00 1907 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
