<HEADLINE> Corning to add union workers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CORNING, N.Y. (AP) - Corning Inc. plans to add as many as 100
union workers at four plants, the first time in six years it has
added union members to its employment rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen A. Mandell Sr., president of Local 1000 of the American
Flint Glass Workers Union, said the hiring plans represent a
turnaround for the union, whose membership dwindled to about 1,600
in recent years. During the 1990s, as many as 300 workers were laid
off at one time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll be up over 3,000 before too long,'' Mandell told the
Elmira Star-Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   The company needs general production and maintenance workers,
machinists, electricians and process technicians for jobs at the
Erwin Ceramics, Big Flats, Fall Brook and Sullivan Park sites.
</P>
<P>
   The new jobs are a result of growth in Corning's businesses and
expansion of some of its Corning-area facilities. Corning Inc., the
region's largest employer, has more than 5,600 on its payroll in
the Twin Tiers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the existing contract, members of the multi-plant unit
make an average of $14.55 an hour and will go to $14.99 an hour
next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
