<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney for convicted harness racer to ask for reduced sentence  </HEADLINE>
By J.J. THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The attorney for a harness racer convicted
of conspiring to fix races said he plans to request a lighter
sentence for his client due to an appellate court decision.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling Wednesday, a state appellate court struck down two
factors Superior Court Judge Patricia Del Bueno Cleary used when
sentencing once-prominent harness racer Richard Wojcio in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling sends the case back to Superior Court for
resentencing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm hopeful the court will reduce the sentence in light of the
appellate court's striking of several of the aggravating factors
(used during sentencing),'' said Wojcio's attorney, Edward Plaza.
''And in light of the impact the decision has had on Mr. Wojcio and
his family.''
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's Office is pleased the court upheld
Wojcio's conviction, spokesman Chuck Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Wojcio was Freehold Raceway's top harness driver in 1995, when
he won 405 races and more than $2.4 million in purse money.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators accused him of conspiring with drivers before
three races in which he had bet. They claimed he helped other
drivers place second or third in two of those races.
</P>
<P>
   A jury convicted Wojcio in 1998 of conspiring to fix races at
Freehold Raceway. He was cleared of charges of fixing races. He was
sentenced to 180 days in Monmouth County Jail, 500 hours of
community service and five years probation.
</P>
<P>
   He was allowed to remain free during his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Ten issues were raised in the appeal, including whether Cleary
should have admitted into evidence certain statements made by
William Bresnahan. Bresnahan, a harness racer, cooperated with
authorities after they confronted him with evidence of his
involvement with race fixing, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court affirmed the admission of Bresnahan's
statements into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But it did agree with the defense's argument that Cleary erred
when she found that four aggravating factors applied when
sentencing Wojcio.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court struck down two of the factors - that there
was a substantial likelihood Wojcio was involved in organized
criminal activities and that the offense involved fraudulent or
deceptive practices committed against state government.
</P>
<P>
   The judges ruled that the definition of organized crime was
mistakenly applied in this case, and that no fraud or deception was
committed against the New Jersey State Racing Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-06-00 1922 </TRAILER>
