<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico President-Elect Feels Snubbed  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's democratic revolution apparently
caught U.S. presidential candidates off-guard.
</P>
<P>
   Both had snubbed overtures from the campaign of Vicente Fox, the
first opposition candidate to win Mexico's presidency in more than
a century, Fox aides said. But they did receive representatives
from his ruling-party opponent.
</P>
<P>
   And that has the Fox campaign seething.
</P>
<P>
   ''The U.S. candidates didn't bet on democracy in Mexico,
although U.S. society did,'' said Carlos Salazar, director of
international relations with Fox's National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   Fox aides said that after Sunday's elections, Al Gore and George
W. Bush both called Fox to offer their congratulations. Both made
several calls before Fox accepted either one.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers said both U.S. candidates were friendly toward the
campaign of Francisco Labastida of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, while spurning Fox's overtures.
</P>
<P>
   Bush met with Labastida's wife and his top foreign policy
adviser during an event in Los Angeles in April. Gore's campaign
maintained close relations with Labastida's through James Carville
and Stanley Greenberg, who were advising both campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But while Bush let Fox advisers meet with two of his top aides,
he wasn't willing to receive a visit from Fox's daughter Ana
Cristina, who will act as first lady for the divorced Fox,
according to the Fox aides.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's representatives wouldn't meet with anyone from the Fox
campaign, the Fox aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Both U.S. campaigns denied they spurned Fox. Bush spokesman
Scott McClellan noted that although Bush did not meet Fox during
the campaign, he had met him previously in his function as governor
as Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Bush looks forward to working with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Jano Cabrera said Gore had ''a very good
conversation with Vicente Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He congratulated him on what he thought was an historic
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera said that Fox told the vice president he was planning to
come to Washington in the near future, and that the two men agreed
to get together.
</P>
<P>
   Relations with the United States are crucial for any Mexican
president. Millions of Mexicans live in the United States, and the
3,000-mile border between the two countries can be a source of
tremendous conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, President Clinton's call did get through on
election night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Fox ''would be welcome here at any time if he would
come up.'' Fox plans to take him up on the offer before his
swearing-in on Dec. 1, although he hasn't set a date yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 1932 </TRAILER>
