<HEADLINE> Navy will repair damage to neighborhood  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WILLOW GROVE, Pa. (AP) - The Navy promised Thursday that it will
repair the downed trees and burned earth where two Navy pilots died
last month during an air show at the Willow Grove Naval Air
Station.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the project will begin this month and should be
completed by early September, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. William J. Dey, 30, of Hightstown, N.J., the pilot, and Lt.
David E. Bergstrom, 31, of Virginia Beach, Va., the radar intercept
officer, were killed June 18. Tens of thousands of spectators
watched in horror as their F-14 Tomcat crashed in a wooded area
just outside the base. The plane came to rest close to nearby
houses. A Navy report on the cause of the crash may take up to a
year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   The crash site, with its sheared trees and scorched earth, is
still off limits, but has attracted frequent observers.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy plans to remove the top 8 inches of topsoil from the
site to remove any remaining fuel, then level the area and replant
trees.
</P>
<P>
   The Tomcat was loaded with 1,300 gallons of fuel when it
crashed, but a Navy spokeswoman said all but 100 gallons burned or
evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   ''They (neighbors) shouldn't have to worry about the ground
water,'' U.S. Environmental Protection Agency spokeswoman Pamela
Reigh said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials believe that Dey maneuvered his plane to avoid
the houses when he crashed. Despite the close call, neighbors
support the base and hope the shows will go on.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials have canceled at least one scheduled Tomcat
demonstration since the crash, saying it was too soon to resume the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ''They shouldn't just give up,'' said Barry Starry of Willow
Grove, who lives near the base. ''Maybe they should not quite do
the maneuvers with the jets so close to the houses that they did
this past time. But, please, let's have the shows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
