<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sale of Avalanche, Nuggets Complete  </HEADLINE>
By MARY WEBB
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- St. Louis real estate developer Stanley Kroenke
completed his $450 million purchase of the Colorado Avalanche, the
Denver Nuggets and the Pepsi Center on Thursday, only 10 weeks
after the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me personally, it's an exciting day. It's something I've
wanted to do all my life, be involved in professional sports,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kroenke, a Wal-Mart heir, owns 40 percent of the NFL's St. Louis
Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been fortunate to be involved for the last seven years.
But, to be able to expand our interests and be involved with
quality organizations, like the (NHL's) Avalanche and the (NBA's)
Nuggets, is certainly a dream come true,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale was a quick turnaround for Kroenke as well as Liberty
Media, which acquired the sports assets when it bought Ascent
Entertainment Group in February. Liberty Media gave itself six
months to sell the teams and 9-month-old arena.
</P>
<P>
   On April 24, Kroenke edged out a bid by Denver Broncos owner Pat
Bowlen, former Broncos quarterback John Elway and New Jersey Devils
owner John McMullen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our stated goal among many things was to find a right,
long-term owner for the fans and city of Denver,'' said Gary
Howard, executive vice president and chief operating officer of
Liberty Media.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were very pleased in April when we made the announcement we
were working with Stan Kroenke and had signed a deal. And
amazingly, two months later, we were able to close that
transaction. I think that's a record onto itself,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Before turning the teams over, Howard challenged Kroenke to
extend Liberty Media's sports success, joking that both teams had
their highest winning percentages under one owner, if only for a
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Kroenke, a 20-year part-time resident of Steamboat Springs, and
the city narrowly missed their targeted close date of June 30 due
to what Kroenke called ''a somewhat unusual lease for a
privately-funded arena.''
</P>
<P>
   The city withheld its approval of the deal until Kroenke agreed
the teams would stay in Denver for at least 25 years, even if he
died.
</P>
<P>
   However, he denied he and the city had clashed on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only issue we had with the city is them waiting on us. We
never had any problem with them,'' Kroenke said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Media retains 6.52 percent interest in the teams and the
arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
