<HEADLINE> Court upholds state's purchase of forest lands  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A state court has upheld the sale of nearly
140,000 acres of forest land in four counties.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit challenging the state's $24.9 million purchase of land
from Champion International Corp. was dismissed as being a
''procedural mess,'' untimely and in the wrong jurisdiction, state
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The state bought 29,000 acres on July 1, 1999 and negotiated the
purchase by a private, North Carolina-based company, Forestland
Group, of another 110,000 acres in conservation easements in
Franklin, St. Lawrence, Lewis and Herkimer counties.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was challenged by a group of citizens and hunting clubs
who claimed the state did not follow proper procedures in acquiring
the land.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Eliot Spitzer and Department of Environmental
Conservation Commissioner John Cahill cheered the decision to
uphold the purchase, what they termed as the largest land
conservation buy in state history.
</P>
<P>
   The Champion land acquisition gives the public access to large
tracts of forest, streams and rivers that had been in private hands
for more than a century. It also allows for continued commercial
logging on land that is covered by conservation easements, Spitzer
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
