<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three plead guilty for illegal wool trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Two people and an India-based company
pleaded guilty to illegally trading woolen shawls made from an
endangered Tibetan antelope, the U.S. Attorney's Office announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ho-McAfee, 49, of Hong Kong, and Janet MacKay-Benton, 42,
of New Egypt, pleaded guilty to violations of the U.S. Endangered
Species Act. Navarang Exports India pleaded guilty to smuggling in
violation of U.S. customs law.
</P>
<P>
   Ho-McAfee and MacKay-Benton, both employees of Cocoon Inc. in
Cliffwood, admitted exporting shahtoosh shawls to Paris from the
United States in March 1995 without filing proper forms with the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, said the U.S. Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Shahtoosh shawls are made from Tibetan antelopes, which are
protected under the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Navarang imported about 300 shahtoosh shawls
into the United States between September 1994 and March 1995. The
company only paid about $1,000 of the import duty for the shawls
valued at $246,400.
</P>
<P>
   It still owes $31,700 in unpaid duty, said the U.S. Attorney's
Office.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer representing Navarang admitted that the company did not
obtain necessary permits from the United States or the country the
shawls originated from, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Ho-McAfee and MacKay-Benton could each face up to six months in
prison and a $25,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Navarang could face up to five years of probation and a $500,000
fine.
</P>
<P>
   They are scheduled to be sentenced in October.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Robert J. Cleary said this case is the first
criminal prosecution involving the endangered antelopes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-06-00 1949 </TRAILER>
