<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Laundering Eyed in Caribbean  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN McNAMARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANOUAN, St. Vincent (AP) -- Wrapping up a summit, Caribbean
leaders pledged to fight money laundering but refused to change tax
laws which have landed much of the region on a blacklist for
allegedly abetting financial crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the 15-nation Caribbean Community said they would
send a strongly worded protest letter to the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development in Paris, which last month
cited five Caribbean nations for not cooperating in the fight
against money laundering and said 15 were hot spots for tax
evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Sir James Mitchell, prime minister of St. Vincent and the
Grenadines and chairman of the summit, condemned the blacklists and
threatened sanctions as ''a direct threat to the region's economic
base and stability'' at a time when revenue from traditional
sources such as bananas, sugar and tourism are flat.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day summit, which concluded Wednesday night, appeared
to highlight the fundamental impotence of the region's small
countries in the face of what Antigua and Barbuda spokesman Ron
Sanders called the OECD's ''highhanded'' move.
</P>
<P>
   ''They deplored the fact that the lists were published with the
objective of tainting jurisdictions in the eyes of the investment
community and the international financial market. They condemned
the actions of the OECD in particular as contrary to the tenets of
a global market economy promoted by (rich) countries,'' said a
summit declaration.
</P>
<P>
   It said the threatened sanctions by the 26-nation OECD -- which
includes the United States and the prosperous nations of Western
Europe -- had ''no basis in international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominican Prime Minister Roosevelt Douglas said most of the
Caribbean countries are insistent on their right to decide on their
own tax laws, which they consider part of the free market economy.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the statement did promise ''to fight money
laundering and all other forms of financial crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean leaders dismissed claims that they aid in tax evasion
as merely a hypocritical effort to recoup revenues and business
that have shifted to the region. ''Tax competition is about whose
treasury gets the money,'' Mitchell said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Britain estimates that it loses about $1.6 billion a year in tax
revenues hidden in offshore tax havens. There are no firm figures
for U.S. losses.
</P>
<P>
   The OECD says lax laws, little oversight and low taxes invite
some of the $600 billion in criminal funds that the United Nations
estimates is hidden from law enforcement officials every year by
such money laundering methods as moving it through offshore
accounts, with about a tenth of that passing through Caribbean
banking centers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 1949 </TRAILER>
