<DOCNO> APW20000706.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Ecstasy Bust, Bjt,350  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The mastermind of a multi-million dollar ecstasy
ring bragged he wanted to give mob turncoat Salvatore ''Sammy the
Bull'' Gravano a taste of his own medicine and have him
''whacked,'' authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Ilan Zarger, was among 17 defendants accused in
Brooklyn of trafficking ecstasy on the East Coast and in Arizona,
where Gravano is facing designer drug-dealing charges in a separate
case.
</P>
<P>
   A complaint filed in federal court claims Zarger was caught on
tape telling an informant he ''had a problem'' with Gravano, the
ex-underboss for the Gambino crime family who admitted killing 19
people.
</P>
<P>
   Zarger said the recent dispute was over the ''selling price for
ecstasy in Arizona.'' He also boasted that he ''was prepared to
have Gravano 'whacked' ... but they were able to resolve the
dispute,'' court papers added.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano is being held on $5 million bond in Arizona, accused in
February of heading the state's largest ecstasy syndicate. He had
been living in suburban Tempe after helping authorities put away
his boss, John Gotti, for life.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Gravano, Larry Hammond, did not immediately
return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Zarger, 30, an Israeli living in Manhattan, was ordered held
without bail. His attorney, Jeffrey Rabin, said he was unaware of
the accusations involving Gravano, but added his client would
''vigorously defend himself against'' the drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities accused Zarger and five other defendants distributed
more than one million ecstasy pills - street value $25 million - in
Brooklyn, Manhattan, Long Island and Arizona. Among the alleged
customers for the psychedelic amphetamine was a violent drug and
robbery crew called the ''Brooklyn Terror Squad.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven members of the crew were charged with dealing drugs and
illegal guns, and of robbing nightclub patrons and owners. Their
crimes allegedly spanned New York City, Philadelphia, Boston,
Washington D.C., Connecticut and New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
