<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Wants Cart Issue Resolved  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEMONT, Ill. (AP) -- At least Casey Martin will finally know,
once and for all, whether he can use a cart during tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour asked the U.S. Supreme Court on Wednesday to review
a lower court ruling that allows Martin to use a cart. Martin, who
has a rare circulatory disease in his right leg, sued the PGA Tour
in 1998 under the Americans With Disabilities Act, a federal
anti-bias act.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's carried on about three years too far. But it's
their right to pursue it as far as they want to,'' Martin said
Thursday afternoon after shooting a 5-over-par 77 in the first
round of the Western Open.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the last straw. So we'll have the final word someday
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, now in summer recess, probably won't decide
until late October whether to take up the case.
</P>
<P>
   Martin earned his tour card in October by finishing in the top
15 on the Nike Tour, but he has struggled in his rookie season. He
has made the cut in only eight of 15 tournaments, and his only
finish in the top 30 was a tie for 17th in the Tucson Open, the
same week the top players were competing in the Match Play
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The court battle, Martin said, hasn't been a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ''It never enters my mind when I'm playing,'' he said. ''It's a
long way away and it's out of my hands. I keep playing golf until
they tell me otherwise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 2100 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000706.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man gets 50 years for slashing woman  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ELIZABETHTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - A 28-year-old man convicted of
robbing, slashing and trying to kill a woman in the apartment they
shared was sentenced to 50 years in prison Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   John Rouse faced a minimum of 10 years in prison for the Nov.
21, 1998 attack on the now-66 year old woman, but the judge noted
his violent past in meting out the stiffer sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He was given a maximum 25-year prison term each for
second-degree attempted murder and first-degree assault, along with
3&AMP;frac12; to seven years for a weapon charge. All three sentences are to
be served at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   For the robbery conviction, Rouse was given a sentence of 25
years, to be served after the other sentences. He also was ordered
to stay away from his victim for the next 43 years and pay a $155
crime-victim assistance fee from his prison wages.
</P>
<P>
   The victim testified that Rouse threatened to kill her and to
cut off her finger to get her rings. The victim also said Rouse
sexually assaulted her, but Essex County Court Judge Andrew
Halloran dropped charges of first-degree rape, first-degree
attempted rape and first-degree sexual abuse because the victim's
testimony contradicted what she told the grand jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
