<HEADLINE> Mother, son charged after plotting son's prison escape with dynamite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WOODBURY, N.J. (AP) - A Thorofare woman bought what she thought
was dynamite for her son to use to escape from a Pennsylvania
prison, authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Marshall Vickers, 51, and her son, Kerry Marshall, 29,
were indicted Thursday in federal court in Philadelphia. Each faces
a charge of conspiracy to receive explosives.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, which was announced at the
Gloucester County Prosecutor's Office here, Marshall, a prisoner in
the Pennsylvania State Correctional Institution at Graterford,
planned to escape using guns and dynamite. He asked his mother to
buy the dynamite for him.
</P>
<P>
   In her efforts in October she met with an undercover agent who
was posing as one of Marshall's friends. The agent offered to sell
Vickers five sticks of dynamite and a Glock 9 mm semiautomatic
pistol, the U.S. Attorney's Office said.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers bought what she thought was the dynamite and gun from
the agent, wrapped the simulated dynamite in birthday wrapping
paper and took it to her home, where she planned to store it until
she visited her son, according to the U.S. Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Marshall and Vickers each face up to 20 years in
prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall is serving a life term for the 1988 murder of a woman
in Philadelphia. Marshall tried to rob the woman at gunpoint as she
sat in a truck selling fish with her 4-year-old son. When the woman
pulled out a gun, Marshall shot and killed her.
</P>
</TEXT>
