<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gymnast Miller Injures Knee  </HEADLINE>
By DANNY BOYD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Olympic gold medalist Shannon Miller injured
her right knee Thursday when she fell during practice for a meet,
and her coach said she ''most likely'' won't compete this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Miller could put weight on the knee and was walking after the
mishap. X-rays showed there wasn't any structural damage or
ligament damage, said Steve Nunno, Miller's longtime coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's basically a sprained knee,'' Nunno said. ''After the
prognosis of no structural damage, I think everybody took a deep
sigh of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller also will have an MRI exam, and Nunno said they'll make a
final determination about Saturday's U.S. Classic after they get
those results. The U.S. Classic is a qualifier for the national
championships, which will be held July 26-29 in St. Louis, but
Miller could petition for a spot at nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ''You never can tell with this kind of an injury. It may look
worse than it was. Hopefully that's the case,'' Nunno said. ''Right
now it looks like she will not (compete).''
</P>
<P>
   Miller got hurt as she was working on a new vault at the end of
practice. Her hand slipped as she pushed off the vault, and she
didn't get as high into the air as she normally does.
</P>
<P>
   She slammed into the mat, landing awkwardly on both of her
knees. Her right knee appeared to take the worst of the fall, Nunno
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a very tough individual and didn't cry a tear,'' he
said. ''The whole time we were driving home, she was very positive.
Up spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the most decorated American gymnast ever, retired after
the 1996 Olympics, where she won two gold medals. She went to
college and got married during her time off, but she decided in
January she wanted a shot at a third Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gymnastics is such a part of my life,'' she told reporters
Thursday. ''It has been for 17 years now and I'm just not ready to
give it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 2149 </TRAILER>
