<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pathmark bondholders to vote on bond debt agreement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARTERET, N.J. (AP) - Pathmark Stores Inc.'s bondholders have
until Friday to vote on an agreement that would eliminate $960
million in bond debt and give them full ownership of the company.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the Carteret subsidiary of Supermarkets General
Holding Corp. will file a prepackaged Chapter 11 bankruptcy and
begin the transfer of Pathmark to the bondholders, company
officials told The Philadelphia Inquirer Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Pathmark would then be a publicly traded company, with almost
all shares held by the bondholders. The company would still have
$600 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   A prepackaged bankruptcy allows for a faster Chapter 11 process
because creditors agree in advance on the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said the result of the bondholders' vote will
be announced next week. They said they don't expect any layoffs or
store closings.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Pathmark reported that it lost $21.2 million in its
first quarter, which ended April 29. That was more than double its
net loss of $9.2 million a year earlier. Sales for the first
quarter, however, were up 2.8 percent to $919.2 million, primarily
because of new stores.
</P>
<P>
   Pathmark operates 136 supermarkets, mostly in the Philadelphia
and New York-New Jersey metropolitan areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
