<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressConvicted New Brunswick Pedophile Toft Refused Parole
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Karl Toft, a convicted pedophile who
sodomized dozens of boys at a New Brunswick reform school, was
refused release into the community Thursday following a National
Parole Board hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the two-person board panel could not agree on whether
Toft still poses a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because your case has been very difficult to assess, we as
board members were not able to unanimously conclude that your risk
is manageable for full parole release,'' Patricia Gutwald said.
</P>
<P>
   Toft will face another parole hearing next month before two
different board members. Both must agree before he can be freed.
</P>
<P>
   Toft was a staff member at the Youth Training Center in
Kingsclear, New Brunswick. In 1992, he was sentenced to 13 years in
prison for 34 sex crimes against boys in his care committed over a
period of three decades.
Kingston's Notorious Prison for Women Shuts Down
</P>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Ontario (AP) -- Kingston's infamous Prison for Women
closed its doors Thursday in a private ceremony marking the end of
a turbulent history at the 66-year-old institution.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Lawrence MacAulay and Corrections Canada head
Ole Ingstrup joined former inmates and employees at the dreary
stone facility, which has been the subject of at least 13 inquiries
and commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The Prison For Women gained notoriety in 1994 when six women
were strip searched and shackled by mostly male guards. Four years
later, each of the women was awarded $50,000 after an investigation
provided the public with a shocking picture of life inside the
maximum-security prison.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation in 1998, conducted by Correctional Service of
Canada, confirmed that 23 women were given the hallucinogen LSD in
a pilot project in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   There had also been several escapes at the prison, and five
suicides between 1988 and 1991.
Imperial Tobacco Launches Lawsuit Against Federal Labeling Law
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Imperial Tobacco filed a lawsuit Thursday that
aims to strike down new federal legislation requiring larger health
warnings on cigarette packages.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Quebec Superior Court, asks for an
immediate halt to the law's requirement that the warnings be big
enough to cover half of a cigarette package.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Canada's largest manufacturer of tobacco, contends
the labeling law is unconstitutional because it infringes on the
corporation's freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   ''These packages belong to us,'' said Michel Descoteaux, an
Imperial Tobacco spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He said the firm, whose brands include Du Maurier and Players,
doesn't object to warning labels but requiring half the package to
contain health messages is excessive.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says the government has not produced any credible
evidence that large warning notices would lead to a reduction in
the number of Canadians who smoke.
Human Rights Laws Toward Seniors Called Discriminatory
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Human rights laws that don't protect people who
choose to keep working after age 65 are discriminatory and will
likely be challenged in court as the population ages, Ontario's
chief human rights commissioner said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While releasing the commission's statistics for last year, Keith
Norton said Ontario policy makers will likely have to extend the
age of protection for workers as the average age of Canadians
continues to grow older.
</P>
<P>
   Although no laws state when Canadians must retire, workers are
only protected from discrimination on the basis of age up to 65,
Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the type of job, mandatory retirement age in Canada
varies depending on the employer, collective agreements and
professions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
