<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Titanic' Clothes Suppliers Slain  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW BARAKAT
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Mother and daughter antiques dealers who
supplied vintage clothes for movies such as ''Titanic'' were found
slain at their homes, and the daughter's ex-husband was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Varner, 50, was found dead in the kitchen of her home
around 7 p.m. Wednesday, shortly after her mother, Suzanne Arena,
79, was found slain in her home in a neighboring county.
</P>
<P>
   Reginald Varner, 53, who was divorced from Susan Varner in 1998
after 20 years of marriage, was arrested after a police officer
stopped him for speeding and saw blood and an ax in the car, police
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Police gave few details of the slayings but did say Susan Varner
apparently had been struck with a blunt instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Varner was being held without bond, and a hearing was set for
Monday. Calls to two attorneys who were appointed Thursday to
represent him were not immediately returned late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The victims owned Suzi's Antiques in this south-central Virginia
town, which supplied vintage clothing for movies with historical
themes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something this town won't get over any time soon,''
said Irene Flowers, co-owner of the Wooden Heart gift shop across
the street from the antiques store. ''It's not just a murder. It's
something out of a Stephen King movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Varner and Arena did extensive work for ''Titanic,'' which
won an Academy Award for best costumes. Among the many items they
provided were the black beaded dress that Kate Winslet wore when
she threatened to jump off the stern of the ship early in the movie
and the jacket that Leonardo DiCaprio threw to the deck as he
rushed to save her.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I saw the movie -- I'm so jaded, because I'm so overworked
-- it was like my heart skipped a beat, I could not believe how
beautiful they were,'' Varner said in 1998. ''We were just
stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   The women spent about half their time traveling around the
country in a van buying clothes. Celebrity clients included Johnny
Cash and his wife, June Carter, who bought a collection of
Victorian clothing from the women for $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of our customers don't treat the shop like a store,''
Varner said in 1998. ''Those who know about us or who have been
here before treat it like a museum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
