<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Chided on Clean-Water Plan  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID A. LIEB
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- Two senators accused the Clinton
administration Thursday of rushing proposed environmental rules in
an attempt to circumvent Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is proposing to regulate
runoff from farms and businesses in an effort to clean up an
estimated 20,000 streams and lakes that do not meet water-quality
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Congress on June 30 passed budget legislation that included
language barring the use of federal money for the new EPA
regulations -- effectively delaying the rules.
</P>
<P>
   But Sens. Blanche Lincoln, D-Ark., and Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark.,
said Thursday the Clinton administration had ordered the EPA to
rush the rules to completion.
</P>
<P>
   If the rules are finalized before Clinton's July 13 deadline to
sign the bill, then Congress's prohibition against money for the
new rules may have no effect, they said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewart declined to say whether the
administration had directed the rules to be speedily implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're examining a number of options to deal with this rider
which we think is ill-advised and undermines some of the
protections for clean water,'' Siewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln said attorneys are studying whether an early imposition
of the rules would negate the spending ban that she and Hutchinson
had inserted into a military appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   The senators contend the EPA is overstepping its authority in
attempting to regulate runoff from farms and other agricultural
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's proposal would require states to submit plans within
15 years to clean up every waterway that fails to meet water
quality standards. Landowners would be required to get a pollution
discharge permit if the EPA found they were contributing to water
quality problems.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has estimated that the program would cost governments
and the private sector less than $100 million. But the General
Accounting Office has disputed that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 2304 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000706.0206 </DOCNO>
