<HEADLINE> Israel Accuses Lebanon of Violations  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Israel accused Lebanon Thursday of giving
''free rein'' to nearly 50 cross-border attacks on Israeli soldiers
and civilians and demanded an immediate end to the violations.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Israel's U.N.
Ambassador Yehuda Lancry called on the Lebanese government ''at
long last'' to deploy its army in the area, disarm the militia
groups, and ''bring peace and security to our common border.''
</P>
<P>
   An annex attached to the letter listed 48 incidents between June
28 and July 4 in which stones or objects were hurled across the
border from the Lebanese side, usually by a few individuals, but on
one occasion by at least 450 people.
</P>
<P>
   Lancry called on the authorities in Beirut to end the violations
and abide by U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of southern
Lebanon as a buffer against guerrilla attacks on northern Israel
from 1985 until its withdrawal on May 24. The U.N. Security Council
endorsed the Israeli pullout on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   On June 26, the U.N. peacekeeping force in Lebanon reported half
a dozen Israeli border violations and on July 3, it reported a
dozen. Diplomats described the violations as minor, involving
Israeli use of roads, installations and equipment now in Lebanese
territory.
</P>
<P>
   But U.N. peacekeepers have not yet reported on any Lebanese
violations of the temporary border between the two nations which
was drawn by U.N. cartographers to verify the Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is pressing for the Lebanese army to deploy to the south
because since the Israeli pullout, Shiite Muslim Hezbollah
guerrillas who fought the Israeli troops for years have moved into
the former occupied zone and taken de facto control. Lancry said
Hezbollah ''participated in some of the attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Lebanese government wants to be sure there are no more
violations of the withdrawal line before giving ''a green light''
for the deployment of its army.
</P>
<P>
   Under 1978 Security Council resolutions, U.N. peacekeeping
troops who verified the Israeli pullout were supposed to deploy to
the border area to help the Lebanese army restore security and
authority in the border zone. But their deployment has also been
delayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
