<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vieques Protesters Choose Jail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Two Independence Party leaders
chose jail over fines Thursday in a protest over the Navy's
practice bombing on Vieques island.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Martin, vice president of the party, and Vance Thomas,
the party's candidate for mayor of San Juan, were ordered to pay
fines of $1,000 and $700 respectively for trespassing when they
invaded the Navy's Vieques training ground on June 26.
</P>
<P>
   They were trying to stop the biggest exercises since an April
1999 bombing accident killed a civilian security guard on the
range.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have the key to get out,'' Judge Hector Lafitte told the
men, inviting them to pay the fines. He did not say how long the
men would have to stay in jail if they chose not to. The maximum
penalty for the offense is $5,000 or six months' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Thomas are among 123 Independence Party members
ordered arrested for breaking into the ground last week. Eight-six
are in jail waiting to go to court. The others haven't been
arrested since warrants were issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders say 50 years of bomb testing has damaged their health
and environment and stunted tourism on Vieques, an island of 9,400
people where 25 percent of workers are unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   l
</P>
</TEXT>
