<HEADLINE> All-Star Ramirez Homers in Minors  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Manny Ramirez was back in the minors
Thursday, hitting a home run to start another rehab stint. Now the
question is how long he'll be with the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, a free agent at the end of the season, went 2-for-5 and
drove in three runs in a doubleheader as the designated hitter for
the Triple-A Buffalo Bisons.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star outfielder was playing for the first time in 19
days because of a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's agent, Jeff Moorad, said Thursday he has had no new
negotiations with Indians general manager John Hart and isn't
expecting the team to make a contract offer before the July 31
trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''John has made it clear that so long as the team is in
contention he's not going to disrupt the chemistry of the club,''
Moorad told The Associated Press in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''July 31 isn't much of a deadline at all.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Ramirez wants to stay in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Moorad, who negotiated Shawn Green's $84 million deal with the
Dodgers, said he knows the Indians can't afford to make Ramirez the
highest-paid player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We understand the team can only pay Manny what it can pay
him,'' Moorad said, ''and still meet the payroll for the rest of
the team. I think it's fair to say Manny will be the highest-paid
player on the Indians or whomever he plays with. Is enough enough
at a certain level? Of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Moorad addressed some recent reports that the Indians were
displeased with how long it has taken Ramirez to return from his
injury, and that Moorad might be urging him not to rush.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hamstrings, as I have learned, are very difficult injuries to
gauge, and Manny is as frustrated as anyone that he's been unable
to help the Indians,'' Moorad said. ''My counsel to him has been,
straight from the beginning, 'Take care of yourself and get back on
the field as soon as possible.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez homered in his second at-bat in Game 1. When he doubled
in two runs in his first at-bat in Game 2, he ran the bases slowly.
Ramirez was lifted for a pinch-hitter in the fourth inning and left
the stadium before the end of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bisons manager Joel Skinner said pulling Ramirez had nothing to
do with his injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had five at-bats and that was plenty,'' Skinner said. ''He
was fine. For his first game back ... he got his work done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, who was elected to start next week's All-Star game but
won't play, was assigned to the Bisons earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He went on the disabled list June 2, retroactive to May 30. An
initial comeback attempt was cut short when he reaggravated the
hamstring injury in the seventh inning of his first game back with
Double-A Akron on June 17.
</P>
<P>
   Before getting hurt, Ramirez was hitting .322 with 13 home runs
and 47 RBIs in 47 games with Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The four-time All-Star finished tied for third in the American
League MVP voting last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
