<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Williams Says 'No' to Tar Heels  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID DROSCHAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- A sign at the Smith Center this week
read: ''Please come home Roy.'' By late Thursday night, the placard
was down and reality had set in on the North Carolina campus.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of returning to his alma mater, Roy Williams decided to
remain at Kansas, turning down former boss and good friend Dean
Smith and what many believed was a dream job for the winningest
coach of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe his devotion to his players impacted his decision
more than anything else,'' North Carolina athletic director Dick
Baddour said. ''If it weren't for that factor we would probably be
having a different press conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Several newspapers reported Thursday that Williams had said
''yes'' to coach one of basketball's more storied programs. Baddour
said that wasn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Roy never told us in a definite way he was coming,'' Baddour
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels had formed no search committee after Bill
Guthridge retired last week following three highly successful years
as Smith's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   They felt they didn't need one. Williams, 49, was the
hand-picked replacement by Smith and many believe there was no way
he could say no to the game's all-time winningest coach.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he did.
</P>
<P>
   Smith did not attend the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Chewning, the chairman of the Educational Foundation, the
school's influential athletic fund-raising organization, said he
wasn't surprised Williams took almost a week to decide on the job
offer from the Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was between him, his heart and his family. People forget
that sometimes,'' Chewning said. ''He's nobody's puppet.''
</P>
<P>
   Baddour said money wasn't a factor. Although he refused to be
specific on contract terms offered Williams, he said Williams had a
great visit to campus over the July 4 holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I even told Coach Smith one time, 'We're not going to leave
any stone unturned. We're going to do everything we can. It's like
Roy Williams doesn't know us,''' Baddour said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't good enough, though, as Williams called Baddour, Smith
and Guthridge about 7 p.m. Thursday to inform each of his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were emotional conversations,'' Baddour said.
</P>
<P>
   What now for the Tar Heels, who went to two Final Fours under
Guthridge? Speculation will turn to Eddie Fogler at South Carolina
and two NBA coaches -- Larry Brown of the Philadelphia 76ers and
George Karl of the Milwaukee Bucks. All three are former Tar Heels
who have remained close to Smith and the program.
</P>
<P>
   Baddour said the school would not limit its search to coaches
with North Carolina ties and had no real timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ''As soon as possible,'' Baddour said of a replacement.
''Anybody who wants to be a candidate can be a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthridge will return from a beach vacation Monday and remain
the school's interim coach until a replacement is found, Baddour
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to identify candidates, but we've got a B plan, a
C plan and a D plan,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 2326 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000706.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Spill Worries Environmentalists  </HEADLINE>
By GILLIAN FLYNN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, R.I. (AP) -- Environmentalists said Thursday they
were worried about the effects of a large oil spill that has killed
several birds and led to a ban on fishing in one of the most
fertile areas of Narragansett Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard said 14,000 gallons of oil has spilled out of a
barge that collided with a tug on Wednesday. Five swans died and 50
Canada geese were found blackened with oil.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is becoming more and more of a serious spill. There may
be quite a few injured birds and ailing wildlife around the bay,''
said John Torgan, Narragansett Bay keeper for the environmental
group Save The Bay. ''This is the most heavily fished area for
lobsters in Narragansett Bay. This will have a serious impact,
there's no way around it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 460-foot-long barge was carrying 3.8 million gallons of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officials thought the oil would remain near the
barge, but there have been reports of oil sheens and tar balls four
miles south of the spill. Lobstermen were asked not to pull up
their traps; oil has coated many of the buoys that mark the traps.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Morin, a state Department of Environmental Management
administrator, said the bay will remain closed for at least a week,
which means losses of $100,000 a day for lobstermen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anytime oil hits the water we have a disaster both
environmentally and economically,'' Morin said.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officials hoped light wind would lessen the spread
of the oil, and crews used vacuum trucks and oil-skimming vessels
to contain the spill.
</P>
<P>
   Penn Maritime Inc., which owns the boats that collided, took
full responsibility for the spill and dispatched 50 workers to
clean the shorelines on foot.
</P>
<P>
   The worst oil spill in Rhode Island history came in 1996, when
828,000 gallons fouled the water, killing more than 9 million
lobsters and leading to a five-month ban on fishing. A $16 million
settlement to restore the Block Island Sound environment damaged by
the spill was announced Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-06-00 2327 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000706.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Arrested for Family Murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARECIBO, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Police on Thursday arrested a man
accused of slashing the throats of his wife and four children.
</P>
<P>
   After a weeklong hunt, an officer acting on a tip found Hector
Mercado Cedeno, 50, near the house in the small mountain town of
Utuado where the killings occurred, Lt. Efrain Muniz said.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Carmen Maldonado Santana, 35, was found with those
of the four children, stabbed and slashed. The children ranged in
age from 1 to 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
